01544 /**
01545  * cvmx_usbdrd#_uahc_dalepena
01546  *
01547  * This register indicates whether a USB endpoint is active in a given configuration or
01548  * interface.
01549  *
01550  * This register can be reset by IOI reset or USBDRD()_UCTL_CTL[UAHC_RST] or
01551  * USBDRD()_UAHC_GCTL[CORESOFTRESET] or
01552  * USBDRD()_UAHC_USBCMD[HCRST] or USBDRD()_UAHC_USBCMD[LHCRST] or
01553  * USBDRD()_UAHC_DCTL[CSFTRST].
01554  */
01555 union cvmx_usbdrdx_uahc_dalepena {
01556     uint32_t u32;
01557     struct cvmx_usbdrdx_uahc_dalepena_s {
01558 #ifdef __BIG_ENDIAN_BITFIELD
01559     uint32_t usbactep                     : 32; /**< This field indicates if a USB endpoint is active in the current configuration
01560                                                          and interface. It applies to USB IN endpoints 0-15 and OUT endpoints 0-15,
01561                                                          with one bit for each of the 32 possible endpoints. Even numbers are for
01562                                                          USB OUT endpoints, and odd numbers are for USB IN endpoints, as
01563                                                          follows:
01564                                                           <0> = USB EP0-OUT.
01565                                                           <1> = USB EP0-IN.
01566                                                           <2> = USB EP1-OUT.
01567                                                           <3> = USB EP1-IN.
01568                                                          The entity programming this register must set bits 0 and 1 because they
01569                                                          enable control endpoints that map to physical endpoints (resources) after
01570                                                          USBReset.
01571                                                          Application software clears these bits for all endpoints (other than EP0-OUT
01572                                                          and EP0-IN) after detecting a USB reset. After receiving SetConfiguration
01573                                                          and SetInterface requests, the application must program endpoint registers
01574                                                          accordingly and set these bits. */
01575 #else
01576     uint32_t usbactep                     : 32;
01577 #endif
01578     } s;
01579     struct cvmx_usbdrdx_uahc_dalepena_s   cn70xx;
01580     struct cvmx_usbdrdx_uahc_dalepena_s   cn70xxp1;
01581     struct cvmx_usbdrdx_uahc_dalepena_s   cn73xx;
01582     struct cvmx_usbdrdx_uahc_dalepena_s   cnf75xx;
01583 };

01668 /**
01669  * cvmx_usbdrd#_uahc_dcfg
01670  *
01671  * This register configures the core in device mode after power-on or after certain control
01672  * commands or enumeration. Do not make changes to this register after initial programming.
01673  *
01674  * This register can be reset by IOI reset or USBDRD()_UCTL_CTL[UAHC_RST].
01675  */
01676 union cvmx_usbdrdx_uahc_dcfg {
01677     uint32_t u32;
01678     struct cvmx_usbdrdx_uahc_dcfg_s {
01679 #ifdef __BIG_ENDIAN_BITFIELD
01680     uint32_t reserved_24_31               : 8;
01681     uint32_t ignorestreampp               : 1;  /**< This bit only affects stream-capable bulk endpoints.
01682                                                          When this bit is set to 0x0 and the controller receives a data packet with the
01683                                                          packet pending (PP) bit set to 0 for OUT endpoints, or it receives an ACK
01684                                                          with the NumP field set to 0 and PP set to 0 for IN endpoints, the core
01685                                                          attempts to search for another stream (CStream) to initiate to the host.
01686                                                          However, there are two situations where this behavior is not optimal:
01687                                                          * When the host is setting PP=0 even though it has not finished the
01688                                                          stream, or.
01689                                                          * When the endpoint on the device is configured with one transfer
01690                                                          resource and therefore does not have any other streams to initiate to the
01691                                                          host.
01692                                                          When this bit is set to 0x1, the core ignores the packet pending bit for the
01693                                                          purposes of stream selection and does not search for another stream when
01694                                                          it receives DP(PP=0) or ACK(NumP=0, PP=0). This can enhance the
01695                                                          performance when the device system bus bandwidth is low */
01696     uint32_t lpmcap                       : 1;  /**< LPM capable.
01697                                                          The application uses this bit to control the controller's core LPM
01698                                                          capabilities. If the core operates as a non-LPM-capable device, it cannot
01699                                                          respond to LPM transactions.
01700                                                            0x0 = LPM capability is not enabled.
01701                                                            0x1 = LPM capability is enabled. */
01702     uint32_t nump                         : 5;  /**< Number of receive buffers.
01703                                                          This bit indicates the number of receive buffers to be reported in the ACK
01704                                                          TP.
01705                                                          The DWC_usb3 controller uses this field if USBDRD()_UAHC_GRXTHRCFG[USBRXPKTCNTSEL]
01706                                                          is set to 0x0. The application can program this value based on RxFIFO size,
01707                                                          buffer sizes programmed in descriptors, and system latency.
01708                                                          For an OUT endpoint, this field controls the number of receive buffers
01709                                                          reported in the NumP field of the ACK TP transmitted by the core. */
01710     uint32_t intrnum                      : 5;  /**< Interrupt number.
01711                                                          Indicates interrupt/EventQ number on which non-endpoint-specific device-related
01712                                                          interrupts (see DEVT) are generated. */
01713     uint32_t reserved_10_11               : 2;
01714     uint32_t devaddr                      : 7;  /**< Device address.
01715                                                          The application must perform the following:
01716                                                           * Program this field after every SetAddress request.
01717                                                           * Reset this field to zero after USB reset. */
01718     uint32_t devspd                       : 3;  /**< Device speed.
01719                                                          Indicates the speed at which the application requires the core to connect, or
01720                                                          the maximum speed the application can support. However, the actual bus
01721                                                          speed is determined only after the chirp sequence is completed, and is
01722                                                          based on the speed of the USB host to which the core is connected.
01723                                                            0x0 = High-speed (USB 2.0 PHY clock is 30 MHz or 60 MHz).
01724                                                            0x1 = Full-speed (USB 2.0 PHY clock is 30 MHz or 60 MHz).
01725                                                            0x4 = SuperSpeed (USB 3.0 PHY clock is 125 MHz or 250 MHz). */
01726 #else
01727     uint32_t devspd                       : 3;
01728     uint32_t devaddr                      : 7;
01729     uint32_t reserved_10_11               : 2;
01730     uint32_t intrnum                      : 5;
01731     uint32_t nump                         : 5;
01732     uint32_t lpmcap                       : 1;
01733     uint32_t ignorestreampp               : 1;
01734     uint32_t reserved_24_31               : 8;
01735 #endif
01736     } s;
01737     struct cvmx_usbdrdx_uahc_dcfg_s       cn70xx;
01738     struct cvmx_usbdrdx_uahc_dcfg_s       cn70xxp1;
01739     struct cvmx_usbdrdx_uahc_dcfg_s       cn73xx;
01740     struct cvmx_usbdrdx_uahc_dcfg_s       cnf75xx;
01741 };

01744 /**
01745  * cvmx_usbdrd#_uahc_dctl
01746  *
01747  * This register controls devlice mode.
01748  *
01749  * This register can be reset by IOI reset or USBDRD()_UCTL_CTL[UAHC_RST].
01750  */
01751 union cvmx_usbdrdx_uahc_dctl {
01752     uint32_t u32;
01753     struct cvmx_usbdrdx_uahc_dctl_s {
01754 #ifdef __BIG_ENDIAN_BITFIELD
01755     uint32_t rs                           : 1;  /**< Run/Stop.
01756                                                          The software writes 1 to this bit to start the device controller operation.
01757                                                          To stop the device controller operation, the software must remove any active
01758                                                          transfers and write 0 to this bit. When the controller is stopped, it sets the
01759                                                          USBDRD()_UAHC_DSTS[DEVCTRLHLT] bit when the core is idle and the lower layer finishes
01760                                                          the disconnect process.
01761                                                          The Run/Stop bit must be used in following cases as specified:
01762                                                             1. After power-on reset and CSR initialization, the software must write 1 to this bit
01763                                                             to start the device controller. The controller does not signal connect to the host
01764                                                             until this bit is set.
01765                                                             2. The software uses this bit to control the device controller to perform a soft
01766                                                             disconnect. When the software writes 0 to this bit, the host does not see that
01767                                                             the device is connected. The device controller stays in the disconnected state
01768                                                             until the software writes 1 to this bit. The minimum duration of keeping this bit
01769                                                             cleared is 30ms in SuperSpeed and 10ms in High/Full/LowSpeed.
01770                                                             If the software attempts a connect after the soft disconnect or detects a
01771                                                             disconnect event, it must set USBDRD()_UAHC_DCTL[ULSTCHNGREQ] to
01772                                                             "Rx.Detect" before reasserting the Run/Stop bit. */
01773     uint32_t csftrst                      : 1;  /**< Core soft reset.
01774                                                          Resets the all clock domains as follows:
01775                                                          * Clears the interrupts and all the CSRs except the following registers:
01776                                                            GCTL, GUCTL, GSTS, GSNPSID, GGPIO, GUID, GUSB2PHYCFGn registers,
01777                                                            GUSB3PIPECTLn registers, DCFG, DCTL, DEVTEN, DSTS.
01778                                                          * All module state machines (except the SoC Bus Slave Unit) are reset to the
01779                                                             IDLE state, and all the TxFIFOs and the RxFIFO are flushed.
01780                                                          * Any transactions on the SoC bus Master are terminated as soon as possible,
01781                                                            after gracefully completing the last data phase of a SoC bus transfer. Any
01782                                                            transactions on the USB are terminated immediately.
01783                                                          The application can write this bit at any time to reset the core. This is a self-clearing
01784                                                          bit; the core clears this bit after all necessary logic is reset in the core,
01785                                                          which may take several clocks depending on the corefs current state. Once this
01786                                                          bit is cleared, the software must wait at least 3 PHY clocks before accessing the
01787                                                          PHY domain (synchronization delay). Typically, software reset is used during
01788                                                          software development and also when you dynamically change the PHY selection
01789                                                          bits in the USB configuration registers listed above. When you change the PHY,
01790                                                          the corresponding clock for the PHY is selected and used in the PHY domain.
01791                                                          Once a new clock is selected, the PHY domain must be reset for proper
01792                                                          operation. */
01793     uint32_t reserved_29_29               : 1;
01794     uint32_t hird_thres                   : 5;  /**< HIRD threshold.
01795                                                          The core asserts output signals utmi_l1_suspend_n and utmi_sleep_n on the basis of this
01796                                                          signal:
01797                                                          * The core asserts utmi_l1_suspend_n to put the PHY into Deep Low-Power
01798                                                            mode in L1 when both of the following are true:
01799                                                            - HIRD value is greater than or equal to the value in HIRD_Thres[3:0]
01800                                                            - HIRD_Thres[4] is set to 1'b1.
01801                                                          * The core asserts utmi_sleep_n on L1 when one of the following is true:
01802                                                            - If the HIRD value is less than HIRD_Thres[3:0] or
01803                                                            - HIRD_Thres[4] is set to 1'b0. */
01804     uint32_t appl1res                     : 1;  /**< LPM response programmed by application.
01805                                                          Handshake response to LPM token specified by device application. Response
01806                                                          depends on USBDRD()_UAHC_DCFG[LPMCAP].
01807                                                           LPMCAP is 0x0 - The core always responds with timeout (that is, no
01808                                                           response).
01809                                                           LPMCAP is 0x1 and this bit is 0:
01810                                                           The core responds with an ACK upon a successful LPM transaction,
01811                                                               which requires all of the following are satisfied:
01812                                                               * There are no PID/CRC5 errors in both the EXT token and the LPM token
01813                                                               (if not true, inactivity results in a timeout ERROR).
01814                                                               * A valid bLinkState = 0001B (L1) is received in the LPM transaction (else
01815                                                               STALL).
01816                                                               * No data is pending in the Transmit FIFO and OUT endpoints not in flow
01817                                                               controlled state (else NYET).
01818                                                           LPMCAP is 0x1 and this bit is 1:
01819                                                          The core responds with an ACK upon a successful LPM, independent
01820                                                              of transmit FIFO status and OUT endpoint flow control state. The LPM
01821                                                              transaction is successful if all of the following are satisfied:
01822                                                              * There are no PID/CRC5 errors in both the EXT token and the LPM token
01823                                                              (else ERROR).
01824                                                              * A valid bLinkState = 0001B (L1) is received in the LPM transaction (else
01825                                                              STALL). */
01826     uint32_t reserved_20_22               : 3;
01827     uint32_t keepconnect                  : 1;  /**< Always write 0. */
01828     uint32_t l1hibernationen              : 1;  /**< Always write 0. */
01829     uint32_t crs                          : 1;  /**< Controller restore state.
01830                                                          This command is similar to the USBDRD()_UAHC_USBCMD[CRS] bit in host mode and
01831                                                          initiates the restore process. When software sets this bit to 1, the controller
01832                                                          immediately sets USBDRD()_UAHC_DSTS[RSS] to 1. When the controller has finished
01833                                                          the restore process, it sets USBDRD()_UAHC_DSTS[RSS] to 0.
01834                                                          Note: When read, this field always returns 0. */
01835     uint32_t css                          : 1;  /**< Controller save state.
01836                                                          This command is similar to the USBDRD()_UAHC_USBCMD[CSS] bit in host mode and
01837                                                          initiates the restore process. When software sets this bit to 1, the controller
01838                                                          immediately sets USBDRD()_UAHC_DSTS[SSS] to 1. When the controller has finished
01839                                                          the save process, it sets USBDRD()_UAHC_DSTS[SSS] to 0.
01840                                                          Note: When read, this field always returns 0. */
01841     uint32_t reserved_13_15               : 3;
01842     uint32_t initu2ena                    : 1;  /**< Initiate U2 enable.
01843                                                           0 = May not initiate U2 (default).
01844                                                           1 = May initiate U2.
01845                                                          On USB reset, hardware clears this bit to 0. Software sets this bit after receiving
01846                                                          SetFeature(U2_ENABLE), and clears this bit when ClearFeature(U2_ENABLE) is
01847                                                          received.
01848                                                          If USBDRD()_UAHC_DCTL[ACCEPTU2ENA] is 0, the link immediately exits U2 state. */
01849     uint32_t acceptu2ena                  : 1;  /**< Accept U2 enable.
01850                                                           0 = Reject U2 except when Force_LinkPM_Accept bit is set (default).
01851                                                           1 = Core accepts transition to U2 state if nothing is pending on the
01852                                                              application side.
01853                                                          On USB reset, hardware clears this bit to 0. Software sets this bit after receiving
01854                                                          a SetConfiguration command. */
01855     uint32_t initu1ena                    : 1;  /**< Initiate U1 enable.
01856                                                           0 = May not initiate U1 (default).
01857                                                           1 = May initiate U1.
01858                                                          On USB reset, hardware clears this bit to 0. Software sets this bit after receiving
01859                                                          SetFeature(U1_ENABLE), and clears this bit when ClearFeature(U1_ENABLE) is
01860                                                          received.
01861                                                          If USBDRD()_UAHC_DCTL[ACCEPTU1ENA] is 0, the link immediately exits U1 state. */
01862     uint32_t acceptu1ena                  : 1;  /**< Accept U1 enable.
01863                                                           0 = Reject U1 except when Force_LinkPM_Accept bit is set (default)
01864                                                           1 = Core accepts transition to U1 state if nothing is pending on the
01865                                                              application side.
01866                                                          On USB reset, hardware clears this bit to 0. Software sets this bit after receiving
01867                                                          a SetConfiguration command. */
01868     uint32_t ulstchngreq                  : 4;  /**< USB/link state change request.
01869                                                          Software writes this field to issue a USB/link state change request. A change in
01870                                                          this field indicates a new request to the core. If software wants to issue the same
01871                                                          request back-to-back, it must write a 0 to this field between the two requests. The
01872                                                          result of the state change request is reflected in USBDRD()_UAHC_DSTS[USBLNKST].
01873                                                          These bits are self-cleared on the MAC Layer exiting suspended state.
01874                                                          If software is updating other fields of the USBDRD()_UAHC_DCTL register and not
01875                                                          intending to force any link state change, then it must write a 0 to this field.
01876                                                          SuperSpeed compliance mode is normally entered and controlled by the remote link
01877                                                          partner. Refer to the USB3 specification. Alternatively, you can force the local link
01878                                                          directly into Compliance mode, by resetting the SuperSpeed link with the
01879                                                          USBDRD()_UAHC_DCTL[RS] bit set to zero. If you then write 0xA to the ULSTCHNGREQ
01880                                                          field and 1 to USBDRD()_UAHC_DCTL[RS], the Link will go to compliance. Once you
01881                                                          are in compliance, you may alternately write 0x0 and 0xA to this field to advance
01882                                                          the compliance pattern.
01883                                                          In SS mode:
01884                                                              0x0 = No Action.
01885                                                              0x4 = SS.Disabled.
01886                                                              0x5 = Rx.Detect.
01887                                                              0x6 = SS.Inactive.
01888                                                              0x8 = Recovery.
01889                                                              0xA = Compliance.
01890                                                              Others = Reserved.
01891                                                          In HS/FS/LS mode:
01892                                                              0x8 = Remote wakeup request.
01893                                                              The remote wakeup request should be issued 2us after the device goes into
01894                                                              suspend state (USBDRD()_UAHC_DSTS[USBLNKST] is 0x3).
01895                                                              Others = Reserved. */
01896     uint32_t tstctl                       : 4;  /**< Test control.
01897                                                          0x0 = Test mode disabled.
01898                                                          0x1 = Test_J mode.
01899                                                          0x2 = Test_K mode.
01900                                                          0x3 = Test_SE0_NAK mode.
01901                                                          0x4 = Test_Packet mode.
01902                                                          0x5 = Test_Force_Enable.
01903                                                          Others = Reserved. */
01904     uint32_t reserved_0_0                 : 1;
01905 #else
01906     uint32_t reserved_0_0                 : 1;
01907     uint32_t tstctl                       : 4;
01908     uint32_t ulstchngreq                  : 4;
01909     uint32_t acceptu1ena                  : 1;
01910     uint32_t initu1ena                    : 1;
01911     uint32_t acceptu2ena                  : 1;
01912     uint32_t initu2ena                    : 1;
01913     uint32_t reserved_13_15               : 3;
01914     uint32_t css                          : 1;
01915     uint32_t crs                          : 1;
01916     uint32_t l1hibernationen              : 1;
01917     uint32_t keepconnect                  : 1;
01918     uint32_t reserved_20_22               : 3;
01919     uint32_t appl1res                     : 1;
01920     uint32_t hird_thres                   : 5;
01921     uint32_t reserved_29_29               : 1;
01922     uint32_t csftrst                      : 1;
01923     uint32_t rs                           : 1;
01924 #endif
01925     } s;
01926     struct cvmx_usbdrdx_uahc_dctl_s       cn70xx;
01927     struct cvmx_usbdrdx_uahc_dctl_s       cn70xxp1;
01928     struct cvmx_usbdrdx_uahc_dctl_s       cn73xx;
01929     struct cvmx_usbdrdx_uahc_dctl_s       cnf75xx;

01933 /**
01934  * cvmx_usbdrd#_uahc_depcmd#
01935  *
01936  * This register enables software to issue physical endpoint-specific commands. This register
01937  * contains command, control, and status fields relevant to the current generic command,
01938  * while the USBDRD()_UAHC_DEPCMDPAR* registers provide command parameters and return
01939  * status information.
01940  *
01941  * Several fields (including CMDTYPE) are write-only, so their read values are undefined. After
01942  * power-on, prior to issuing the first endpoint command, the read value of this register is
01943  * undefined. In particular, [CMDACT] may be set after power-on. In this case, it is safe
01944  * to issue an endpoint command.
01945  *
01946  * This register can be reset by IOI reset or USBDRD()_UCTL_CTL[UAHC_RST] or
01947  * USBDRD()_UAHC_GCTL[CORESOFTRESET] or
01948  * USBDRD()_UAHC_USBCMD[HCRST] or USBDRD()_UAHC_USBCMD[LHCRST] or
01949  * USBDRD()_UAHC_DCTL[CSFTRST].
01950  */
01951 union cvmx_usbdrdx_uahc_depcmdx {
01952     uint32_t u32;
01953     struct cvmx_usbdrdx_uahc_depcmdx_s {
01954 #ifdef __BIG_ENDIAN_BITFIELD
01955     uint32_t commandparam                 : 16; /**< Command or event parameters.
01956                                                          When this register is written:
01957                                                            Command parameters:
01958                                                              For start transfer command:
01959                                                              _  - [31:16]: StreamID. The USB StreamID assigned to this transfer
01960                                                              For start transfer command applied to an isochronous endpoint:
01961                                                              _  - [31:16]: StartMicroFramNum: Indicates the (micro)frame number to
01962                                                                which the first TRB applies
01963                                                              For update transfer, end transfer, and start new configuration
01964                                                              commands:
01965                                                              _  - [22:16]: Transfer resource index (XferRscIdx). The hardware-assigned
01966                                                                transfer resource index for the transfer, which was returned
01967                                                                in response to the Start Transfer command. The application
01968                                                                software-assigned transfer resource index for a Start New
01969                                                                Configuration command.
01970                                                          When this register is read:
01971                                                              For XferNotReady, XferComplete, and stream events on bulk endpoints:
01972                                                              _  - [31:16]: StreamID. Applies only to bulk endpoints that support streams. This
01973                                                                           indicates the StreamID of the transfer for which the event is
01974                                                                           generated
01975                                                              For XferInProgress:
01976                                                              _  - [31:16]: Isochronous microframe number (IsocMicroFrameNum): Indicates the
01977                                                                           microframe number of the beginning of the interval that generated
01978                                                                           the XferInProgress event (debug purposes only)
01979                                                              For XferNotReady events on Isochronous Endpoints:
01980                                                              _  - [31:16]: Isochronous microframe number (IsocMicroFrameNum). Indicates the
01981                                                                           microframe number during which the endpoint was not ready
01982                                                                Note: controller core represents USB bus time as a 14-bit value on the bus and also
01983                                                                in the DSTS register (USBDRD()_UAHC_DSTS[SOFFN]), but as a 16-bit value in the
01984                                                                XferNotReady event. Use the 16-bit value to interact with isochronous endpoints via
01985                                                                the StartXfer command. The extra two bits that the controller core produces will be
01986                                                                necessary for handling wrap-around conditions in the interaction between software
01987                                                                and hardware.
01988                                                             For all EPCmdCmplt events
01989                                                             _  - [27:24]: Command type. The command type that completed (Valid only in a DEPEVT
01990                                                                             event. Undefined when read from the
01991                                                                             USBDRD()_UAHC_DEPCMD()[COMMANDPARAM] field).
01992                                                             For EPCmdCmplt event in response to start transfer command:
01993                                                             _  - [22:16]: Transfer resource index (XferRscIdx). The internal hardware transfer
01994                                                                             resource index assigned to this transfer. This index must be used in
01995                                                                             all update transfer and end transfer commands. */
01996     uint32_t cmdstatus                    : 4;  /**< Command completion status.
01997                                                          Additional information about the completion of this command is available in
01998                                                          this field.
01999                                                          Within an XferNotReady event:
02000                                                          _ [15]: Indicates the reason why the XferNotReady event is generated:
02001                                                          _ [15] = 0: XferNotActive: Host initiated a transfer, but the requested transfer is not
02002                                                                present in the hardware.
02003                                                          _ [15] = 1: XferActive: Host initiated a transfer, the transfer is present, but no valid
02004                                                          TRBs
02005                                                                are available
02006                                                          _ [14]: Not Used
02007                                                          _ [13:12]: For control endpoints, indicates what stage was requested when the transfer was
02008                                                            not ready:
02009                                                          _ [13:12] = 0x1: Control data request
02010                                                          _ [13:12] = 0x2: Control status request
02011                                                          Within an XferComplete or XferInProgress event:
02012                                                          _ [15]: LST bit of the completed TRB (XferComplete only)
02013                                                          _ [15]: MissedIsoc: Indicates the interval did not complete successfully (XferInProgress
02014                                                            only)
02015                                                          _ [14]: IOC bit of the TRB that completed.
02016                                                          _ [13]: Indicates the TRB completed with a short packet reception or the last packet of an
02017                                                            isochronous interval
02018                                                          _ [12]: Reserved.
02019                                                            If the host aborts the data stage of a control transfer, software may receive a
02020                                                            XferComplete event with the EventStatus field equal to 0. This is a valid event
02021                                                            that must be processed as a part of the control transfer programming model.
02022                                                          Within a stream event:
02023                                                          _ [15:12] = 0x2: StreamNotFound: This stream event is issued when the stream-capable
02024                                                          endpoint
02025                                                                performed a search in its transfer resource cache, but could not find an active
02026                                                                and ready stream.
02027                                                          _ [15:12] = 0x1: StreamFound: This stream event is issued when the stream-capable endpoint
02028                                                          found
02029                                                                an active and ready stream in its transfer resource cache, and initiated traffic for
02030                                                                that stream to the host. The ID of the selected Stream is in the EventParam field.
02031                                                          In response to a Start Transfer command:
02032                                                          _ [15:12] = 0x2: Indicates expiry of the bus time reflected in the Start Transfer command.
02033                                                          _ [15:12] = 0x1: Indicates there is no transfer resource available on the endpoint.
02034                                                          In response to a Set Transfer Resource (DEPXFERCFG) command:
02035                                                          _ [15:12] = 0x1: Indicates an error has occurred because software is requesting more
02036                                                          transfer
02037                                                                resources to be assigned than have been configured in the hardware.
02038                                                          In response to a end transfer command:
02039                                                          _ [15:12] = 0x1: Indicates an invalid transfer resource was specified. */
02040     uint32_t hipri_forcerm                : 1;  /**< HighPriority: Only valid for start transfer command.
02041                                                          ForceRM: Only valid for end transfer command. */
02042     uint32_t cmdact                       : 1;  /**< Software sets this bit to 1 to enable the device endpoint controller to
02043                                                          execute the generic command.
02044                                                          The device controller sets this bit to 0 when [CMDSTATUS] is valid and
02045                                                          the endpoint is ready to accept another command. This does not imply that
02046                                                          all the effects of the previously-issued command have taken place. */
02047     uint32_t reserved_9_9                 : 1;
02048     uint32_t cmdioc                       : 1;  /**< Command interrupt on complete.
02049                                                          When this bit is set, the device controller issues a generic endpoint
02050                                                          command complete event after executing the command. Note that this
02051                                                          interrupt is mapped to DEPCFG.IntrNum. When the DEPCFG command is
02052                                                          executed, the command interrupt on completion goes to the interrupt
02053                                                          pointed by the USBDRD()_UAHC_DCFG[INTRNUM] in the current command.
02054                                                          Note: This field must not set to 1 if the USBDRD()_UAHC_DCTL[RS] field is 0. */
02055     uint32_t reserved_4_7                 : 4;
02056     uint32_t cmdtyp                       : 4;  /**< Command type.
02057                                                          Specifies the type of command the software driver is requesting the core to
02058                                                          perform.
02059                                                          0x0 = Reserved.
02060                                                          0x1 = Set endpoint configuration (64 or 96-bit parameter).
02061                                                          0x2 = Set endpoint transfer resource configuration (32-bit parameter).
02062                                                          0x3 = Get endpoint state (no parameter needed).
02063                                                          0x4 = Set stall (no parameter needed).
02064                                                          0x5 = Clear stall (see set stall, no parameter needed).
02065                                                          0x6 = Start transfer (64-bit parameter).
02066                                                          0x7 = Update transfer (no parameter needed).
02067                                                          0x8 = End transfer (no parameter needed).
02068                                                          0x9 = Start new configuration (no parameter needed). */
02069 #else
02070     uint32_t cmdtyp                       : 4;
02071     uint32_t reserved_4_7                 : 4;
02072     uint32_t cmdioc                       : 1;
02073     uint32_t reserved_9_9                 : 1;
02074     uint32_t cmdact                       : 1;
02075     uint32_t hipri_forcerm                : 1;
02076     uint32_t cmdstatus                    : 4;
02077     uint32_t commandparam                 : 16;
02078 #endif
02079     } s;
02080     struct cvmx_usbdrdx_uahc_depcmdx_s    cn70xx;
02081     struct cvmx_usbdrdx_uahc_depcmdx_s    cn70xxp1;
02082     struct cvmx_usbdrdx_uahc_depcmdx_s    cn73xx;
02083     struct cvmx_usbdrdx_uahc_depcmdx_s    cnf75xx;
02084 };
02085 typedef union cvmx_usbdrdx_uahc_depcmdx cvmx_usbdrdx_uahc_depcmdx_t;

02326 /**
02327  * cvmx_usbdrd#_uahc_dsts
02328  *
02329  * This register indicates the status of the device controller with respect to USB-related
02330  * events.
02331  *
02332  * This register can be reset by IOI reset or USBDRD()_UCTL_CTL[UAHC_RST].
02333  */
02334 union cvmx_usbdrdx_uahc_dsts {
02335     uint32_t u32;
02336     struct cvmx_usbdrdx_uahc_dsts_s {
02337 #ifdef __BIG_ENDIAN_BITFIELD
02338     uint32_t reserved_30_31               : 2;
02339     uint32_t dcnrd                        : 1;  /**< Device controller not ready.
02340                                                          Will always read-as-zero. */
02341     uint32_t sre                          : 1;  /**< Save/restore error.
02342                                                          This bit is currently not supported. */
02343     uint32_t reserved_26_27               : 2;
02344     uint32_t rss                          : 1;  /**< Restore state status.
02345                                                          This bit is similar to the USBDRD()_USBSTS[RSS] in host mode.
02346                                                          When the controller has finished the restore process, it will complete the
02347                                                          command by setting RSS to 0.
02348                                                          Will always read-as-zero. */
02349     uint32_t sss                          : 1;  /**< Save state status.
02350                                                          This bit is similar to the USBDRD()_UAHC_USBSTS[SSS] in host mode.
02351                                                          When the controller has finished the save process, it will complete the
02352                                                          command by setting SSS to 0.
02353                                                          Will always read-as-zero. */
02354     uint32_t coreidle                     : 1;  /**< Core idle.
02355                                                          The bit indicates that the core finished transferring all RxFIFO data to
02356                                                          system memory, writing out all completed descriptors, and all event counts
02357                                                          are zero.
02358                                                          Note: While testing for Reset values, mask out the read value. This bit
02359                                                          represents the changing state of the core and does not hold a static value. */
02360     uint32_t devctrlhlt                   : 1;  /**< Device controller halted.
02361                                                          When 1, the core does not generate device events.
02362                                                          - This bit is set to 0 when the USBDRD()_UAHC_DCTL[RS] register is set to 1.
02363                                                          - The core sets this bit to 1 when, after software sets USBDRD()_UAHC_DCTL[RS] to 0,
02364                                                          the core is
02365                                                            idle and the lower layer finishes the disconnect process. */
02366     uint32_t usblnkst                     : 4;  /**< USB/link state.
02367                                                          In SuperSpeed mode, uses LTSSM State:
02368                                                             0x0 = U0.
02369                                                             0x1 = U1.
02370                                                             0x2 = U2.
02371                                                             0x3 = U3.
02372                                                             0x4 = SS_DIS.
02373                                                             0x5 = RX_DET.
02374                                                             0x6 = SS_INACT.
02375                                                             0x7 = POLL.
02376                                                             0x8 = RECOV.
02377                                                             0x9 = HRESET.
02378                                                             0xa = CMPLY.
02379                                                             0xb = LPBK.
02380                                                             0xf = Resume/Reset.
02381                                                             others: Reserved.
02382                                                          In High/Full/LowSpeed mode:
02383                                                             0x0 = On state.
02384                                                             0x2 = Sleep (L1) state.
02385                                                             0x3 = Suspend (L2) state.
02386                                                             0x4 = Disconnected state (Default state).
02387                                                             0x5 = Early Suspend state.
02388                                                             others: Reserved.
02389                                                          The link state resume/reset indicates that the core received a resume or
02390                                                          USB reset request from the host while the link was in hibernation. Software
02391                                                          must write '8' (recovery) to the USBDRD()_UAHC_DCTL[ULSTCHNGREQ] field to acknowledge
02392                                                          the resume/reset request. */
02393     uint32_t rxfifoempty                  : 1;  /**< RxFIFO Empty Indication. */
02394     uint32_t soffn                        : 14; /**< Frame/MicroFrame number of the received SOF.
02395                                                          When the core is operating at high-speed:
02396                                                            <16:6> = Frame number.
02397                                                            <5:3> = Microframe number.
02398                                                          When the core is operating at full-speed:
02399                                                            <16:14> = Not used, software can ignore these 3 bits.
02400                                                            <13:3> = Frame number. */
02401     uint32_t connectspd                   : 3;  /**< Connected speed.
02402                                                          Indicates the speed at which the controller core has come up after speed
02403                                                          detection through a chirp sequence.
02404                                                           0x0 = High-speed (PHY clock is running at 60 MHz).
02405                                                           0x1 = Full-speed (PHY clock is running at 60 MHz).
02406                                                           0x2 = Low-speed  (not supported).
02407                                                           0x3 = Full-speed (PHY clock is running at 48 MHz).
02408                                                           0x4 = SuperSpeed (PHY clock is running at 125 or 250 MHz). */
02409 #else
02410     uint32_t connectspd                   : 3;
02411     uint32_t soffn                        : 14;
02412     uint32_t rxfifoempty                  : 1;
02413     uint32_t usblnkst                     : 4;
02414     uint32_t devctrlhlt                   : 1;
02415     uint32_t coreidle                     : 1;
02416     uint32_t sss                          : 1;
02417     uint32_t rss                          : 1;
02418     uint32_t reserved_26_27               : 2;
02419     uint32_t sre                          : 1;
02420     uint32_t dcnrd                        : 1;
02421     uint32_t reserved_30_31               : 2;
02422 #endif
02423     } s;
02424     struct cvmx_usbdrdx_uahc_dsts_s       cn70xx;
02425     struct cvmx_usbdrdx_uahc_dsts_s       cn70xxp1;

02517 /**
02518  * cvmx_usbdrd#_uahc_gbuserraddr
02519  *
02520  * When the AXI master bus returns error response, the SoC bus error is generated. In the host
02521  * mode, the host_system_err port indicates this condition. In addition, it is also indicated in
02522  * USBDRD()_UAHC_USBSTS[HSE]. Due to the nature of AXI, it is possible that multiple AXI
02523  * transactions
02524  * are active at a time. The host controller does not keep track of the start address of all
02525  * outstanding transactions. Instead, it keeps track of the start address of the DMA transfer
02526  * associated with all active transactions. It is this address that is reported in
02527  * USBDRD()_UAHC_GBUSERRADDR when a bus error occurs. For example, if the host controller
02528  * initiates a DMA
02529  * transfer to write 1 k of packet data starting at buffer address 0xABCD0000, and this DMA is
02530  * broken up into multiple 256 B bursts on the AXI, then if a bus error occurs on any of these
02531  * associated AXI transfers, USBDRD()_UAHC_GBUSERRADDR reflects the DMA start address of
02532  * 0xABCD0000
02533  * regardless of which AXI transaction received the error.
02534  *
02535  * This register can be reset by IOI reset or with USBDRD()_UCTL_CTL[UAHC_RST].
02536  */
02537 union cvmx_usbdrdx_uahc_gbuserraddr {
02538     uint64_t u64;
02539     struct cvmx_usbdrdx_uahc_gbuserraddr_s {
02540 #ifdef __BIG_ENDIAN_BITFIELD
02541     uint64_t busaddr                      : 64; /**< Bus address. Contains the first bus address that encountered an SoC bus error. It is valid
02542                                                          when the USBDRD()_UAHC_GSTS[BUSERRADDRVLD] = 1. It can only be cleared by resetting the
02543                                                          core. */
02544 #else
02545     uint64_t busaddr                      : 64;
02546 #endif
02547     } s;
02548     struct cvmx_usbdrdx_uahc_gbuserraddr_s cn70xx;
02549     struct cvmx_usbdrdx_uahc_gbuserraddr_s cn70xxp1;
02550     struct cvmx_usbdrdx_uahc_gbuserraddr_s cn73xx;
02551     struct cvmx_usbdrdx_uahc_gbuserraddr_s cnf75xx;
02552 };
02553 typedef union cvmx_usbdrdx_uahc_gbuserraddr cvmx_usbdrdx_uahc_gbuserraddr_t;
02554 
02555 /**
02556  * cvmx_usbdrd#_uahc_gctl
02557  *
02558  * This register can be reset by IOI reset or with USBDRD()_UCTL_CTL[UAHC_RST].
02559  *
02560  */
02561 union cvmx_usbdrdx_uahc_gctl {
02562     uint32_t u32;
02563     struct cvmx_usbdrdx_uahc_gctl_s {
02564 #ifdef __BIG_ENDIAN_BITFIELD
02565     uint32_t pwrdnscale                   : 13; /**< Power down scale. The USB3 suspend-clock input replaces pipe3_rx_pclk as a clock source to
02566                                                          a small part of the USB3 core that operates when the SuperSpeed PHY is in its lowest power
02567                                                          (P3) state, and therefore does not provide a clock. This field specifies how many suspend-
02568                                                          clock periods fit into a 16 kHz clock period. When performing the division, round up the
02569                                                          remainder.
02570                                                          For example, when using an 32-bit PHY and 25-MHz suspend clock, PWRDNSCALE = 25000 kHz/16
02571                                                          kHz = 1563 (rounded up).
02572                                                          The minimum suspend-clock frequency is 32 KHz, and maximum suspend-clock frequency is 125
02573                                                          MHz.
02574                                                          The LTSSM uses suspend clock for 12-ms and 100-ms timers during suspend mode. According to
02575                                                          the USB 3.0 specification, the accuracy on these timers is 0% to +50%. 12 ms + 0~+50%
02576                                                          accuracy = 18 ms (Range is 12 ms - 18 ms)
02577                                                          100 ms + 0~+50% accuracy = 150 ms (Range is 100 ms - 150 ms).
02578                                                          The suspend clock accuracy requirement is:
02579                                                          _ (12,000/62.5) * (GCTL[31:19]) * actual suspend_clk_period should be between 12,000 and
02580                                                          18,000
02581                                                          _ (100,000/62.5) * (GCTL[31:19]) * actual suspend_clk_period should be between 100,000 and
02582                                                          150,000
02583                                                          For example, if your suspend_clk frequency varies from 7.5 MHz to 10.5 MHz, then the value
02584                                                          needs to programmed is: power down scale = 10500/16 = 657 (rounded up; and fastest
02585                                                          frequency used). */
02586     uint32_t masterfiltbypass             : 1;  /**< Master filter bypass. Not relevant for Cavium's configuration. */
02587     uint32_t bypssetaddr                  : 1;  /**< Bypass SetAddress in Device Mode.
02588                                                          Always set to 0. */
02589     uint32_t u2rstecn                     : 1;  /**< If the SuperSpeed connection fails during POLL or LMP exchange, the device connects
02590                                                          at non-SuperSpeed mode. If this bit is set, then device attempts three more times to
02591                                                          connect at SuperSpeed, even if it previously failed to operate in SuperSpeed mode.
02592                                                          This bit is only applicable in device mode. */
02593     uint32_t frmscldwn                    : 2;  /**< Frame scale down. Scales down device view of a SOF/USOF/ITP duration.
02594                                                          For SuperSpeed/high-speed mode:
02595                                                          0x0 = Interval is 125 us.
02596                                                          0x1 = Interval is 62.5 us.
02597                                                          0x2 = Interval is 31.25 us.
02598                                                          0x3 = Interval is 15.625 us.
02599                                                          For full speed mode, the scale down value is multiplied by 8. */
02600     uint32_t prtcapdir                    : 2;  /**< 0x1 = for Host configurations.
02601                                                          0x2 = for Device configurations. */
02602     uint32_t coresoftreset                : 1;  /**< Core soft reset: 1 = soft reset to core, 0 = no soft reset.
02603                                                          Clears the interrupts and all the USBDRD()_UAHC_* CSRs except the
02604                                                          following registers: USBDRD()_UAHC_GCTL, USBDRD()_UAHC_GUCTL, USBDRD()_UAHC_GSTS,
02605                                                          USBDRD()_UAHC_GRLSID, USBDRD()_UAHC_GGPIO, USBDRD()_UAHC_GUID,
02606                                                          USBDRD()_UAHC_GUSB2PHYCFG(),
02607                                                          USBDRD()_UAHC_GUSB3PIPECTL().
02608                                                          When you reset PHYs (using USBDRD()_UAHC_GUSB2PHYCFG() or
02609                                                          USBDRD()_UAHC_GUSB3PIPECTL()), you must keep the core in reset state until PHY
02610                                                          clocks are stable. This controls the bus, RAM, and MAC domain resets. */
02611     uint32_t sofitpsync                   : 1;  /**< Synchronize ITP to reference clock. In host mode, if this bit is set to:
02612                                                          0 = The core keeps the UTMI/ULPI PHY on the first port in non-suspended state whenever
02613                                                          there is a SuperSpeed port that is not in Rx.Detect, SS.Disable, and U3 state.
02614                                                          1 = The core keeps the UTMI/ULPI PHY on the first port in non-suspended state whenever the
02615                                                          other non-SuperSpeed ports are not in suspended state.
02616                                                          This feature is useful because it saves power by suspending UTMI/ULPI when SuperSpeed only
02617                                                          is active and it helps resolve when the PHY does not transmit a host resume unless it is
02618                                                          placed in suspend state.
02619                                                          USBDRD()_UAHC_GUSB2PHYCFG()[SUSPHY] eventually decides to put the UTMI/ULPI PHY in to
02620                                                          suspend
02621                                                          state. In addition, when this bit is set to 1, the core generates ITP off of the REF_CLK-
02622                                                          based counter. Otherwise, ITP and SOF are generated off of UTMI/ULPI_CLK[0] based counter.
02623                                                          To program the reference clock period inside the core, refer to
02624                                                          USBDRD()_UAHC_GUCTL[REFCLKPER].
02625                                                          If you do not plan to ever use this feature or the
02626                                                          USBDRD()_UAHC_GFLADJ[GFLADJ_REFCLK_LPM_SEL]
02627                                                          feature, the minimum frequency for the ref_clk can be as low as 32 KHz. You can connect
02628                                                          the
02629                                                          SUSPEND_CLK (as low as 32 KHz) to REF_CLK.
02630                                                          If you plan to enable hardware-based LPM (PORTPMSC[HLE] = 1), this feature cannot be used.
02631                                                          Turn off this feature by setting this bit to zero and use the
02632                                                          USBDRD()_UAHC_GFLADJ[GFLADJ_REFCLK_LPM_SEL] feature.
02633                                                          If you set this bit to 1, the USBDRD()_UAHC_GUSB2PHYCFG() [U2_FREECLK_EXISTS] bit
02634                                                          must be set to 0. */
02635     uint32_t u1u2timerscale               : 1;  /**< Disable U1/U2 timer scaledown. If set to 1, along with SCALEDOWN = 0x1, disables the scale
02636                                                          down of U1/U2 inactive timer values.
02637                                                          This is for simulation mode only. */
02638     uint32_t debugattach                  : 1;  /**< Debug attach. When this bit is set:
02639                                                          * SuperSpeed link proceeds directly to the polling-link state (USBDRD()_UAHC_DCTL[RS] = 1)
02640                                                          without checking remote termination.
02641                                                          * Link LFPS polling timeout is infinite.
02642                                                          * Polling timeout during TS1 is infinite (in case link is waiting for TXEQ to finish). */
02643     uint32_t ramclksel                    : 2;  /**< RAM clock select. Always keep set to 0x0. */
02644     uint32_t scaledown                    : 2;  /**< Scale-down mode. When scale-down mode is enabled for simulation, the core uses scaled-down
02645                                                          timing values, resulting in faster simulations. When scale-down mode is disabled, actual
02646                                                          timing values are used. This is required for hardware operation.
02647                                                          High-speed/full-speed/low-speed modes:
02648                                                          0x0 = Disables all scale-downs. Actual timing values are used.
02649                                                          0x1 = Enables scale-down of all timing values. These include:
02650                                                          * Speed enumeration.
02651                                                          * HNP/SRP.
02652                                                          * Suspend and resume.
02653                                                          0x2 = N/A
02654                                                          0x3 = Enables bits <0> and <1> scale-down timing values.
02655                                                          SuperSpeed mode:
02656                                                          0x0 = Disables all scale-downs. Actual timing values are used.
02657                                                          0x1 = Enables scaled down SuperSpeed timing and repeat values including:
02658                                                          * Number of TxEq training sequences reduce to eight.
02659                                                          * LFPS polling burst time reduce to 100 ns.
02660                                                          * LFPS warm reset receive reduce to 30 us. */
02661     uint32_t disscramble                  : 1;  /**< Disable scrambling. Transmit request to link partner on next transition to recovery or polling. */
02662     uint32_t u2exit_lfps                  : 1;  /**< LFPS U2 exit.
02663                                                          0 = The link treats 248 ns LFPS as a valid U2 exit.
02664                                                          1 = The link waits for 8 us of LFPS before it detects a valid U2 exit.
02665                                                          This bit is added to improve interoperability with a third party host controller. This
02666                                                          host controller in U2 state while performing receiver detection generates an LFPS glitch
02667                                                          of about 4s duration. This causes the device to exit from U2 state because the LFPS filter
02668                                                          value is 248 ns. With the new functionality enabled, the device can stay in U2 while
02669                                                          ignoring this glitch from the host controller. */
02670     uint32_t reserved_1_1                 : 1;
02671     uint32_t dsblclkgtng                  : 1;  /**< Disable clock gating. When set to 1 and the core is in low power mode, internal clock
02672                                                          gating is disabled, which means the clocks are always running. This bit can be set to 1
02673                                                          after power-up reset. */
02674 #else
02675     uint32_t dsblclkgtng                  : 1;
02676     uint32_t reserved_1_1                 : 1;
02677     uint32_t u2exit_lfps                  : 1;
02678     uint32_t disscramble                  : 1;
02679     uint32_t scaledown                    : 2;
02680     uint32_t ramclksel                    : 2;
02681     uint32_t debugattach                  : 1;
02682     uint32_t u1u2timerscale               : 1;
02683     uint32_t sofitpsync                   : 1;
02684     uint32_t coresoftreset                : 1;
02685     uint32_t prtcapdir                    : 2;
02686     uint32_t frmscldwn                    : 2;
02687     uint32_t u2rstecn                     : 1;
02688     uint32_t bypssetaddr                  : 1;
02689     uint32_t masterfiltbypass             : 1;
02690     uint32_t pwrdnscale                   : 13;
02691 #endif
02692     } s;
02693     struct cvmx_usbdrdx_uahc_gctl_s       cn70xx;
02694     struct cvmx_usbdrdx_uahc_gctl_s       cn70xxp1;
02695     struct cvmx_usbdrdx_uahc_gctl_s       cn73xx;
02696     struct cvmx_usbdrdx_uahc_gctl_s       cnf75xx;
02697 };

02937 /**
02938  * cvmx_usbdrd#_uahc_gdmahlratio
02939  *
02940  * This register specifies the relative priority of the SuperSpeed FIFOs with respect to the
02941  * high-speed/full-speed/low-speed FIFOs. The DMA arbiter prioritizes the high-speed/full-speed
02942  * /low-speed round-robin arbiter group every DMA high-low priority ratio grants as indicated in
02943  * the register separately for TX and RX.
02944  *
02945  * To illustrate, consider that all FIFOs are requesting access simultaneously, and the ratio is
02946  * 4. SuperSpeed gets priority for four packets, high-speed/full-speed/low-speed gets priority
02947  * for one packet, SuperSpeed gets priority for four packets, high-speed/full-speed/low-speed
02948  * gets priority for one packet, and so on.
02949  *
02950  * If FIFOs from both speed groups are not requesting access simultaneously then:
02951  * * If SuperSpeed got grants four out of the last four times, then high-speed/full-speed/
02952  * low-speed get the priority on any future request.
02953  * * If high-speed/full-speed/low-speed got the grant last time, SuperSpeed gets the priority on
02954  * the next request.
02955  *
02956  * If there is a valid request on either SuperSpeed or high-speed/full-speed/low-speed, a grant
02957  * is always awarded; there is no idle.
02958  *
02959  * This register can be reset by IOI reset or with USBDRD()_UCTL_CTL[UAHC_RST].
02960  */

02983 /**
02984  * cvmx_usbdrd#_uahc_gevntadr#
02985  *
02986  * This register holds the event buffer DMA address pointer. Software must initialize this
02987  * address once during power-on initialization. Software must not change the value of this
02988  * register after it is initialized.
02989  * Software must only use the GEVNTCOUNTn register for event processing. The lower n bits of the
02990  * address must be USBDRD()_UAHC_GEVNTSIZ()[EVNTSIZ]-aligned.
02991  *
02992  * This register can be reset by IOI reset,
02993  * or USBDRD()_UCTL_CTL[UAHC_RST],
02994  * or USBDRD()_UAHC_GCTL[CORESOFTRESET],
02995  * or USBDRD()_UAHC_USBCMD[HCRST], or USBDRD()_UAHC_USBCMD[LHCRST].

03002                                                          for the Event Buffer. During operation, hardware does not update
03003                                                          this address. */
03004 #else
03005     uint64_t evntadr                      : 64;
03006 #endif
03007     } s;

03015 /**
03016  * cvmx_usbdrd#_uahc_gevntcount#
03017  *
03018  * This register holds the number of valid bytes in the event buffer. During initialization,
03019  * software must initialize the count by writing 0 to the event count field. Each time the
03020  * hardware writes a new event to the Event Buffer, it increments this count. Most events
03021  * are four bytes, but some events may span over multiple four byte entries. Whenever the
03022  * count is greater than zero, the hardware raises the corresponding interrupt
03023  * line (depending on the USBDRD()_UAHC_GEVNTSIZ()[EVNTINTMASK]). On an interrupt, software
03024  * processes one or more events out of the event buffer. Afterwards, software must write the
03025  * event count field with the number of bytes it processed.
03026  *
03027  * Clock crossing delays may result in the interrupt's continual assertion after software
03028  * acknowledges the last event. Therefore, when the interrupt line is asserted, software must
03029  * read the GEVNTCOUNT register and only process events if the GEVNTCOUNT is greater than 0.
03030  *
03031  * This register can be reset by IOI reset,
03032  * or USBDRD()_UCTL_CTL[UAHC_RST],
03033  * or USBDRD()_UAHC_GCTL[CORESOFTRESET],
03034  * or USBDRD()_UAHC_USBCMD[HCRST], or USBDRD()_UAHC_USBCMD[LHCRST].
03035  */
03036 union cvmx_usbdrdx_uahc_gevntcountx {
03037     uint32_t u32;
03038     struct cvmx_usbdrdx_uahc_gevntcountx_s {
03039 #ifdef __BIG_ENDIAN_BITFIELD
03040     uint32_t reserved_16_31               : 16;
03041     uint32_t evntcount                    : 16; /**< When read, returns the number of valid events in the event buffer (in bytes).
03042                                                          When written, hardware decrements the count by the value written.
03043                                                          The interrupt line remains high when count is not 0. */
03044 #else
03045     uint32_t evntcount                    : 16;
03046     uint32_t reserved_16_31               : 16;
03047 #endif
03048     } s;
03049     struct cvmx_usbdrdx_uahc_gevntcountx_s cn70xx;
03050     struct cvmx_usbdrdx_uahc_gevntcountx_s cn70xxp1;
03051     struct cvmx_usbdrdx_uahc_gevntcountx_s cn73xx;
03052     struct cvmx_usbdrdx_uahc_gevntcountx_s cnf75xx;
03053 };
03054 typedef union cvmx_usbdrdx_uahc_gevntcountx cvmx_usbdrdx_uahc_gevntcountx_t;
03055 
03056 /**
03057  * cvmx_usbdrd#_uahc_gevntsiz#
03058  *
03059  * This register holds the event buffer size and the event interrupt mask bit. During power-on
03060  * initialization, software must initialize the size with the number of bytes allocated for
03061  * the event buffer. The event interrupt mask will mask the interrupt, but events are still
03062  * queued. After configuration, software must preserve the event buffer size value when
03063  * changing the event interrupt mask.
03064  *
03065  * This register can be reset by IOI reset,
03066  * or USBDRD()_UCTL_CTL[UAHC_RST],
03067  * or USBDRD()_UAHC_GCTL[CORESOFTRESET],
03068  * or USBDRD()_UAHC_USBCMD[HCRST], or USBDRD()_UAHC_USBCMD[LHCRST].
03069  */
03070 union cvmx_usbdrdx_uahc_gevntsizx {
03071     uint32_t u32;
03072     struct cvmx_usbdrdx_uahc_gevntsizx_s {
03073 #ifdef __BIG_ENDIAN_BITFIELD
03074     uint32_t evntintmask                  : 1;  /**< When set to 1, this prevents the interrupt from being generated.
03075                                                          However, even when the mask is set, the events are queued. */
03076     uint32_t reserved_16_30               : 15;
03077     uint32_t evntsiz                      : 16; /**< Holds the size of the event buffer in bytes; must be a multiple of
03078                                                          four. This is programmed by software once during initialization.
03079                                                          The minimum size of the event buffer is 32 bytes. */
03080 #else
03081     uint32_t evntsiz                      : 16;
03082     uint32_t reserved_16_30               : 15;
03083     uint32_t evntintmask                  : 1;
03084 #endif
03085     } s;
03086     struct cvmx_usbdrdx_uahc_gevntsizx_cn70xx {
03087 #ifdef __BIG_ENDIAN_BITFIELD
03088     uint32_t evntintmask                  : 1;  /**< When set to 1, this prevents the interrupt from being generated.
03089                                                          However, even when the mask is set, the events are queued. */
03090     uint32_t reserved_30_16               : 15;
03091     uint32_t evntsiz                      : 16; /**< Holds the size of the event buffer in bytes; must be a multiple of
03092                                                          four. This is programmed by software once during initialization.
03093                                                          The minimum size of the event buffer is 32 bytes. */
03094 #else
03095     uint32_t evntsiz                      : 16;
03096     uint32_t reserved_30_16               : 15;
03097     uint32_t evntintmask                  : 1;
03098 #endif
03099     } cn70xx;
03100     struct cvmx_usbdrdx_uahc_gevntsizx_cn70xx cn70xxp1;
03101     struct cvmx_usbdrdx_uahc_gevntsizx_cn70xx cn73xx;
03102     struct cvmx_usbdrdx_uahc_gevntsizx_cn70xx cnf75xx;
