03106 /**
03107  * cvmx_usbdrd#_uahc_gfladj
03108  *
03109  * This register provides options for the software to control the core behavior with respect to
03110  * SOF (start of frame) and ITP (isochronous timestamp packet) timers and frame timer
03111  * functionality. It provides the option to override the sideband signal fladj_30mhz_reg. In
03112  * addition, it enables running SOF or ITP frame timer counters completely off of the REF_CLK.
03113  * This facilitates hardware LPM in host mode with the SOF or ITP counters being run off of the
03114  * REF_CLK signal.
03115  *
03116  * This register can be reset by IOI reset or with USBDRD()_UCTL_CTL[UAHC_RST].
03117  */
03118 union cvmx_usbdrdx_uahc_gfladj {
03119     uint32_t u32;
03120     struct cvmx_usbdrdx_uahc_gfladj_s {
03121 #ifdef __BIG_ENDIAN_BITFIELD
03122     uint32_t gfladj_refclk_240mhzdecr_pls1 : 1; /**< This field indicates that the decrement value that the controller applies for each REF_CLK
03123                                                          must be GFLADJ_REFCLK_240MHZ_DECR and GFLADJ_REFCLK_240MHZ_DECR +1 alternatively on each
03124                                                          REF_CLK. Set this bit to 1 only if [GFLADJ_REFCLK_LPM_SEL] is set to 1 and the fractional
03125                                                          component of 240/ref_frequency is greater than or equal to 0.5.
03126                                                          Example:
03127                                                          If the REF_CLK is 19.2 MHz then:
03128                                                          * USBDRD()_UAHC_GUCTL[REFCLKPER] = 52.
03129                                                          * [GFLADJ_REFCLK_240MHZ_DECR] = (240/19.2) = 12.5.
03130                                                          * [GFLADJ_REFCLK_240MHZDECR_PLS1] = 1.
03131                                                          If the REF_CLK is 24 MHz then:
03132                                                          * USBDRD()_UAHC_GUCTL[REFCLKPER] = 41.
03133                                                          * [GFLADJ_REFCLK_240MHZ_DECR] = (240/24) = 10.
03134                                                          * [GFLADJ_REFCLK_240MHZDECR_PLS1] = 0. */
03135     uint32_t gfladj_refclk_240mhz_decr    : 7;  /**< This field indicates the decrement value that the controller applies for each REF_CLK in
03136                                                          order to derive a frame timer in terms of a 240-MHz clock. This field must be programmed
03137                                                          to a nonzero value only if [GFLADJ_REFCLK_LPM_SEL] is set to 1.
03138                                                          The value is derived as follows:
03139                                                          _ [GFLADJ_REFCLK_240MHZ_DECR] = 240/ref_clk_frequency
03140                                                          Examples:
03141                                                          If the REF_CLK is 24 MHz then:
03142                                                          * USBDRD()_UAHC_GUCTL[REFCLKPER] = 41.
03143                                                          * [GFLADJ_REFCLK_240MHZ_DECR] = 240/24 = 10.
03144                                                          If the REF_CLK is 48 MHz then:
03145                                                          * USBDRD()_UAHC_GUCTL[REFCLKPER] = 20.
03146                                                          * [GFLADJ_REFCLK_240MHZ_DECR] = 240/48 = 5.
03147                                                          If the REF_CLK is 17 MHz then:
03148                                                          * USBDRD()_UAHC_GUCTL[REFCLKPER] = 58.
03149                                                          * [GFLADJ_REFCLK_240MHZ_DECR] = 240/17 = 14. */
03150     uint32_t gfladj_refclk_lpm_sel        : 1;  /**< This bit enables the functionality of running SOF/ITP counters on the REF_CLK.
03151                                                          This bit must not be set to 1 if USBDRD()_UAHC_GCTL[SOFITPSYNC] = 1. Similarly, if
03152                                                          [GFLADJ_REFCLK_LPM_SEL] = 1, USBDRD()_UAHC_GCTL[SOFITPSYNC] must not be set to 1.
03153                                                          When [GFLADJ_REFCLK_LPM_SEL] = 1 the overloading of the suspend control of the USB 2.0
03154                                                          first
03155                                                          port PHY (UTMI) with USB 3.0 port states is removed. Note that the REF_CLK frequencies
03156                                                          supported in this mode are 16/17/19.2/20/24/39.7/40 MHz. */
03157     uint32_t reserved_22_22               : 1;
03158     uint32_t gfladj_refclk_fladj          : 14; /**< This field indicates the frame length adjustment to be applied when SOF/ITP counter is
03159                                                          running off of the REF_CLK. This register value is used to adjust:.
03160                                                          * ITP interval when USBDRD()_UAHC_GCTL[SOFITPSYNC] = 1
03161                                                          * both SOF and ITP interval when [GFLADJ_REFCLK_LPM_SEL] = 1.
03162                                                          This field must be programmed to a nonzero value only if [GFLADJ_REFCLK_LPM_SEL] = 1 or
03163                                                          USBDRD()_UAHC_GCTL[SOFITPSYNC] = 1.
03164                                                          The value is derived as below:
03165                                                          _ FLADJ_REF_CLK_FLADJ = ((125000/ref_clk_period_integer) - (125000/ref_clk_period)) *
03166                                                          ref_clk_period
03167                                                          where,
03168                                                          * the ref_clk_period_integer is the integer value of the REF_CLK period got by truncating
03169                                                          the decimal (fractional) value that is programmed in USBDRD()_UAHC_GUCTL[REFCLKPER].
03170                                                          * the ref_clk_period is the REF_CLK period including the fractional value.
03171                                                          Examples:
03172                                                          If the REF_CLK is 24 MHz then:
03173                                                          * USBDRD()_UAHC_GUCTL[REFCLKPER] = 41.
03174                                                          * GLADJ_REFCLK_FLADJ = ((125000/41) -
03175                                                          (125000/41.6666)) * 41.6666 = 2032 (ignoring the fractional value).
03176                                                          If the REF_CLK is 48 MHz then:
03177                                                          * USBDRD()_UAHC_GUCTL[REFCLKPER] = 20.
03178                                                          * GLADJ_REFCLK_FLADJ = ((125000/20) -
03179                                                          (125000/20.8333)) * 20.8333 = 5208 (ignoring the fractional value). */
03180     uint32_t gfladj_30mhz_reg_sel         : 1;  /**< This field selects whether to use the input signal fladj_30mhz_reg or the [GFLADJ_30MHZ]
03181                                                          to
03182                                                          adjust the frame length for the SOF/ITP. When this bit is set to, 1, the controller uses
03183                                                          [GFLADJ_30MHZ] value 0x0, the controller uses the input signal fladj_30mhz_reg value. */
03184     uint32_t reserved_6_6                 : 1;
03185     uint32_t gfladj_30mhz                 : 6;  /**< This field indicates the value that is used for frame length adjustment instead of
03186                                                          considering from the sideband input signal fladj_30mhz_reg. This enables post-silicon
03187                                                          frame length adjustment in case the input signal fladj_30mhz_reg is connected to a wrong
03188                                                          value or is not valid. The controller uses this value if [GFLADJ_30MHZ_REG_SEL] = 1 and
03189                                                          the
03190                                                          SOF/ITP counters are running off of UTMI(ULPI) clock ([GFLADJ_REFCLK_LPM_SEL] = 0 and
03191                                                          USBDRD()_UAHC_GCTL[SOFITPSYNC] is 1 or 0). For details on how to set this value, refer to
03192                                                          section 5.2.4 Frame Length Adjustment Register (FLADJ) of the xHCI Specification. */
03193 #else
03194     uint32_t gfladj_30mhz                 : 6;
03195     uint32_t reserved_6_6                 : 1;
03196     uint32_t gfladj_30mhz_reg_sel         : 1;
03197     uint32_t gfladj_refclk_fladj          : 14;
03198     uint32_t reserved_22_22               : 1;
03199     uint32_t gfladj_refclk_lpm_sel        : 1;
03200     uint32_t gfladj_refclk_240mhz_decr    : 7;
03201     uint32_t gfladj_refclk_240mhzdecr_pls1 : 1;
03202 #endif
03203     } s;
03204     struct cvmx_usbdrdx_uahc_gfladj_s     cn70xx;
03205     struct cvmx_usbdrdx_uahc_gfladj_s     cn70xxp1;
03206     struct cvmx_usbdrdx_uahc_gfladj_s     cn73xx;
03207     struct cvmx_usbdrdx_uahc_gfladj_s     cnf75xx;
03208 };
03209 typedef union cvmx_usbdrdx_uahc_gfladj cvmx_usbdrdx_uahc_gfladj_t;

03364 #else

03546  * This debug register gives information on which event caused the hibernation exit. These
03547  * registers are for debug purposes. They provide debug information on the internal status and
03548  * state machines. Global debug registers have design-specific information, and are used by for
03549  * debugging purposes. These registers are not intended to be used by the customer. If any debug
03550  * assistance is needed for the silicon, contact customer support with a dump of these registers.
03551  *
03552  * This register can be reset by IOI reset or with USBDRD()_UCTL_CTL[UAHC_RST].

03561                                                          bit<12> = Overcurrent detected.

03571                                                          bit<3> = Disconnect detected.

03573                                                          bit<5> = ID change detected.
03574                                                          bit<6> = SRP request detected.
03575                                                          bit<7> = ULPI interrupt detected.
03576                                                          bit<8> = USB reset detected.
03577                                                          bit<9> = Resume detected changed. */

03702 /**
03703  * cvmx_usbdrd#_uahc_grxfifoprihst
03704  *
03705  * This register specifies the relative DMA priority level among the host RXFIFOs (one per USB
03706  * bus instance) within the associated speed group (SuperSpeed or high-speed/full-speed/
03707  * low-speed). When multiple RXFIFOs compete for DMA service at a given time, the RXDMA arbiter
03708  * grants access on a packet-basis in the following manner:
03709  *
03710  * Among the FIFOs in the same speed group (SuperSpeed or high-speed/full-speed/low-speed):
03711  * * High-priority RXFIFOs are granted access using round-robin arbitration.
03712  * * Low-priority RXFIFOs are granted access using round-robin arbitration only after high-
03713  * priority
03714  * RXFIFOs have no further processing to do (i.e., either the RXQs are empty or the corresponding
03715  * RXFIFOs do not have the required data).
03716  *
03717  * The RX DMA arbiter prioritizes the SuperSpeed group or high-speed/full-speed/low-speed group
03718  * according to the ratio programmed in
03719  * USBDRD()_UAHC_GDMAHLRATIO.
03720  *
03721  * For scatter-gather packets, the arbiter grants successive DMA requests to the same FIFO until
03722  * the entire packet is completed. The register size corresponds to the number of configured USB
03723  * bus instances; for example, in the default configuration, there are 3 USB bus instances (1
03724  * SuperSpeed, 1 high-speed, and 1 full-speed/low-speed).
03725  *
03726  * This register can be reset by IOI reset or with USBDRD()_UCTL_CTL[UAHC_RST].
03727  */
03728 union cvmx_usbdrdx_uahc_grxfifoprihst {
03729     uint32_t u32;
03730     struct cvmx_usbdrdx_uahc_grxfifoprihst_s {
03731 #ifdef __BIG_ENDIAN_BITFIELD
03732     uint32_t reserved_3_31                : 29;
03733     uint32_t rx_priority                  : 3;  /**< Each register bit[n] controls the priority (1 = high, 0 = low) of RXFIFO[n] within a speed group. */
03734 #else
03735     uint32_t rx_priority                  : 3;
03736     uint32_t reserved_3_31                : 29;
03737 #endif
03738     } s;
03739     struct cvmx_usbdrdx_uahc_grxfifoprihst_s cn70xx;
03740     struct cvmx_usbdrdx_uahc_grxfifoprihst_s cn70xxp1;
03741     struct cvmx_usbdrdx_uahc_grxfifoprihst_s cn73xx;
03742     struct cvmx_usbdrdx_uahc_grxfifoprihst_s cnf75xx;
03743 };
03744 typedef union cvmx_usbdrdx_uahc_grxfifoprihst cvmx_usbdrdx_uahc_grxfifoprihst_t;
03745 
03746 /**
03747  * cvmx_usbdrd#_uahc_grxfifosiz#
03748  *
03749  * The application can program the internal RAM start address/depth of the each RxFIFO as shown
03750  * below. It is recommended that software use the default value. In Host mode, per-port registers
03751  * are implemented. One register per FIFO.
03752  *
03753  * Reset values = 0:[0x0000_0084] 1:[0x0084_0104] 2:[0x0188_0180].
03754  *
03755  * This register can be reset by IOI reset or with USBDRD()_UCTL_CTL[UAHC_RST].
03756  */
03757 union cvmx_usbdrdx_uahc_grxfifosizx {
03758     uint32_t u32;
03759     struct cvmx_usbdrdx_uahc_grxfifosizx_s {
03760 #ifdef __BIG_ENDIAN_BITFIELD
03761     uint32_t rxfstaddr                    : 16; /**< RxFIFOn RAM start address. This field contains the memory start address for RxFIFOn. The
03762                                                          reset value is derived from configuration parameters. */
03763     uint32_t rxfdep                       : 16; /**< RxFIFOn depth. This value is in terms of RX RAM Data width.
03764                                                          minimum value = 0x20, maximum value = 0x4000. */
03765 #else
03766     uint32_t rxfdep                       : 16;
03767     uint32_t rxfstaddr                    : 16;
03768 #endif
03769     } s;
03770     struct cvmx_usbdrdx_uahc_grxfifosizx_s cn70xx;
03771     struct cvmx_usbdrdx_uahc_grxfifosizx_s cn70xxp1;
03772     struct cvmx_usbdrdx_uahc_grxfifosizx_s cn73xx;
03773     struct cvmx_usbdrdx_uahc_grxfifosizx_s cnf75xx;
03774 };
03775 typedef union cvmx_usbdrdx_uahc_grxfifosizx cvmx_usbdrdx_uahc_grxfifosizx_t;
03776 
03777 /**
03778  * cvmx_usbdrd#_uahc_grxthrcfg
03779  *
03780  * In a normal case, an RX burst starts as soon as 1-packet space is available. This works well
03781  * as long as the system bus is faster than the USB3.0 bus (a 1024-bytes packet takes ~2.2 us on
03782  * the USB bus in SuperSpeed mode). If the system bus latency is larger than 2.2 us to access a
03783  * 1024-byte packet, then starting a burst on 1-packet condition leads to an early abort of the
03784  * burst causing unnecessary performance reduction. This register allows the configuration of
03785  * threshold and burst size control. This feature is enabled by USBRXPKTCNTSEL.
03786  *
03787  * Receive Path:
03788  * * The RX threshold is controlled by USBRXPKTCNT and the RX burst size is controlled by
03789  * USBMAXRXBURSTSIZE.
03790  * * Selecting optimal RX FIFO size, RX threshold, and RX burst size avoids RX burst aborts due
03791  * to overrun if the system bus is slower than USB. Once in a while overrun is OK, and there is
03792  * no functional issue.
03793  * * Some devices do not support terminating ACK retry. With these devices, host cannot set ACK=0
03794  * and Retry=0 and do retry later and you have to retry immediately. For such devices, minimize
03795  * retry due to underrun. Setting threshold and burst size guarantees this.
03796  * A larger RX threshold affects the performance since the scheduler is idle during this time.
03797  *
03798  * This register can be reset by IOI reset or with USBDRD()_UCTL_CTL[UAHC_RST].
03799  */
03800 union cvmx_usbdrdx_uahc_grxthrcfg {
03801     uint32_t u32;
03802     struct cvmx_usbdrdx_uahc_grxthrcfg_s {
03803 #ifdef __BIG_ENDIAN_BITFIELD
03804     uint32_t reserved_30_31               : 2;
03805     uint32_t usbrxpktcntsel               : 1;  /**< USB receive-packet-count enable. Enables/disables the USB reception multipacket
03806                                                          thresholding:
03807                                                          0 = the core can only start reception on the USB when the RX FIFO has space for at least
03808                                                          one packet.
03809                                                          1 = the core can only start reception on the USB when the RX FIFO has space for at least
03810                                                          USBRXPKTCNT amount of packets.
03811                                                          This mode is only used for SuperSpeed.
03812                                                          In device mode, setting this bit to 1 also enables the functionality of reporting
03813                                                          NUMP in the ACK TP based on the RX FIFO space instead of reporting a fixed NUMP derived
03814                                                          from USBDRD()_UAHC_DCFG[NUMP]. */
03815     uint32_t reserved_28_28               : 1;
03816     uint32_t usbrxpktcnt                  : 4;  /**< USB receive-packet count.
03817                                                          In host-mode, specifies space (in number of packets) that must be available in
03818                                                          the RX FIFO before the core can start the corresponding USB RX transaction (burst).
03819                                                          In device mode, specifies the space (in number of packets) that must be available in
03820                                                          the RX FIFO before the core can send ERDY for a flow-controlled endpoint.
03821                                                          This field is only valid when [USBRXPKTCNTSEL] = 1. The valid values are from 0x1 to 0xF.
03822                                                          This field must be <= [USBMAXRXBURSTSIZE]. */
03823     uint32_t usbmaxrxburstsize            : 5;  /**< USB maximum receive-burst size. In host-mode, specifies the maximum bulk IN burst the core
03824                                                          should do. When the system bus is slower than the USB, RX FIFO can overrun during a long
03825                                                          burst.
03826                                                          Program a smaller value to this field to limit the RX burst size that the core can do. It
03827                                                          only applies to SuperSpeed Bulk, Isochronous, and Interrupt IN endpoints in the host mode.
03828                                                          In device mode, specified the NUMP value that will be sent in ERDy for an OUT endpoint.
03829                                                          This field is only valid when [USBRXPKTCNTSEL] = 1. The valid values are from 0x1 to 0x10. */
03830     uint32_t reserved_0_18                : 19;
03831 #else
03832     uint32_t reserved_0_18                : 19;
03833     uint32_t usbmaxrxburstsize            : 5;
03834     uint32_t usbrxpktcnt                  : 4;
03835     uint32_t reserved_28_28               : 1;
03836     uint32_t usbrxpktcntsel               : 1;
03837     uint32_t reserved_30_31               : 2;
03838 #endif
03839     } s;
03840     struct cvmx_usbdrdx_uahc_grxthrcfg_s  cn70xx;
03841     struct cvmx_usbdrdx_uahc_grxthrcfg_s  cn70xxp1;
03842     struct cvmx_usbdrdx_uahc_grxthrcfg_s  cn73xx;
03843     struct cvmx_usbdrdx_uahc_grxthrcfg_s  cnf75xx;
03844 };
03845 typedef union cvmx_usbdrdx_uahc_grxthrcfg cvmx_usbdrdx_uahc_grxthrcfg_t;

03998 /**
03999  * cvmx_usbdrd#_uahc_gtxfifopridev
04000  *
04001  * This register specifies the relative DMA priority level among the Device TXFIFOs (one per IN
04002  * endpoint).
04003  * Each register bit[n] controls the priority (1: high, 0: low) of each TXFIFO[n]. When multiple
04004  * TXFIFOs compete for DMA service at a given time (i.e., multiple TXQs contain TX DMA requests
04005  * and their corresponding TXFIFOs have space available), the TX DMA arbiter grants access on a
04006  * packet-basis in the following manner:
04007  *
04008  *   1. High-priority TXFIFOs are granted access using round-robin arbitration
04009  *
04010  *   2. Low-priority TXFIFOs are granted access using round-robin arbitration only after the
04011  *      high-priority TXFIFOs have no further processing to do (i.e., either the TXQs are empty
04012  *      or the corresponding TXFIFOs are full).
04013  *
04014  * For scatter-gather packets, the arbiter grants successive DMA requests to the same FIFO until
04015  * the entire packet is completed.
04016  *
04017  * When configuring periodic IN endpoints, software must set register bit[n]=1, where n is the
04018  * TXFIFO assignment. This ensures that the DMA for isochronous or interrupt IN endpoints are
04019  * prioritized over bulk or control IN endpoints.
04020  *
04021  * This register is present only when the core is configured to operate in the device mode
04022  * (includes DRD and OTG modes). The register size corresponds to the number of Device IN
04023  * endpoints.
04024  *
04025  * This register can be reset by IOI reset or with USBDRD()_UCTL_CTL[UAHC_RST],
04026  * or USBDRD()_UAHC_GCTL[CORESOFTRESET].
04027  */
04028 union cvmx_usbdrdx_uahc_gtxfifopridev {
04029     uint32_t u32;
04030     struct cvmx_usbdrdx_uahc_gtxfifopridev_s {
04031 #ifdef __BIG_ENDIAN_BITFIELD
04032     uint32_t reserved_4_31                : 28;
04033     uint32_t tx_priority                  : 4;  /**< Each register bit[n] controls the priority (1: high, 0: low) of TXFIFO[n] within a speed
04034                                                          group. */
04035 #else
04036     uint32_t tx_priority                  : 4;
04037     uint32_t reserved_4_31                : 28;
04038 #endif
04039     } s;
04040     struct cvmx_usbdrdx_uahc_gtxfifopridev_s cn70xx;
04041     struct cvmx_usbdrdx_uahc_gtxfifopridev_s cn70xxp1;
04042     struct cvmx_usbdrdx_uahc_gtxfifopridev_s cn73xx;
04043     struct cvmx_usbdrdx_uahc_gtxfifopridev_s cnf75xx;
04044 };
04045 typedef union cvmx_usbdrdx_uahc_gtxfifopridev cvmx_usbdrdx_uahc_gtxfifopridev_t;

04047 /**
04048  * cvmx_usbdrd#_uahc_gtxfifoprihst
04049  *
04050  * This register specifies the relative DMA priority level among the Host TXFIFOs (one per USB
04051  * bus instance) within the associated speed group (SuperSpeed or HighSpeed/FullSpeed/LowSpeed).
04052  * When multiple TXFIFOs compete for DMA service at a given time, the TXDMA arbiter grants access
04053  * on a packet-basis in the following manner:
04054  *
04055  *   1. Among the FIFOs in the same speed group (SuperSpeed or HighSpeed/FullSpeed/LowSpeed):
04056  *
04057  * _   a. High-priority TXFIFOs are granted access using round-robin arbitration
04058  *
04059  * _   b. Low-priority TXFIFOs are granted access using round-robin arbitration only after the
04060  *        high priority TXFIFOs have no further processing to do (i.e., either the TXQs are empty
04061  *        or thecorresponding TXFIFOs are full).
04062  *
04063  *   2. The TX DMA arbiter prioritizes the SuperSpeed group or HighSpeed/FullSpeed/LowSpeed group
04064  *      according to the ratio programmed in the USBDRD()_UAHC_GDMAHLRATIO register.
04065  *
04066  * For scatter-gather packets, the arbiter grants successive DMA requests to the same FIFO until
04067  * the entire packet is completed.
04068  * The register size corresponds to the number of configured USB bus instances; for example, in
04069  * the default configuration, there are 3 USB bus instances (1 SuperSpeed, 1 HighSpeed, and 1
04070  * FullSpeed/LowSpeed).
04071  *
04072  * This register can be reset by IOI reset or with USBDRD()_UCTL_CTL[UAHC_RST],
04073  * or USBDRD()_UAHC_GCTL[CORESOFTRESET].
04074  */
04075 union cvmx_usbdrdx_uahc_gtxfifoprihst {
04076     uint32_t u32;
04077     struct cvmx_usbdrdx_uahc_gtxfifoprihst_s {
04078 #ifdef __BIG_ENDIAN_BITFIELD
04079     uint32_t reserved_3_31                : 29;
04080     uint32_t tx_priority                  : 3;  /**< Each register bit n controls the priority (1: high, 0: low) of TX FIFO<n> within a speed
04081                                                          group. */
04082 #else
04083     uint32_t tx_priority                  : 3;
04084     uint32_t reserved_3_31                : 29;
04085 #endif
04086     } s;
04087     struct cvmx_usbdrdx_uahc_gtxfifoprihst_s cn70xx;
04088     struct cvmx_usbdrdx_uahc_gtxfifoprihst_s cn70xxp1;
04089     struct cvmx_usbdrdx_uahc_gtxfifoprihst_s cn73xx;
04090     struct cvmx_usbdrdx_uahc_gtxfifoprihst_s cnf75xx;
04091 };

04126 /**
04127  * cvmx_usbdrd#_uahc_gtxthrcfg
04128  *
04129  * In a normal case, a TX burst starts as soon as one packet is prefetched. This works well as
04130  * long as the system bus is faster than the USB3.0 bus (a 1024-bytes packet takes ~2.2 us on the
04131  * USB bus in SuperSpeed mode). If the system bus latency is larger than 2.2 us to access a
04132  * 1024-byte packet, then starting a burst on 1-packet condition leads to an early abort of the
04133  * burst causing unnecessary performance reduction. This register allows the configuration of
04134  * threshold and burst size control. This feature is enabled by [USBTXPKTCNTSEL].
04135  *
04136  * Transmit path:
04137  * * The TX threshold is controlled by [USBTXPKTCNT], and the TX burst size is controlled by
04138  * [USBMAXTXBURSTSIZE].
04139  * * Selecting optimal TX FIFO size, TX threshold, and TX burst size avoids TX burst aborts due
04140  * to an underrun if the system bus is slower than USB. Once in a while an underrun is OK, and
04141  * there is no functional issue.
04142  * * A larger threshold affects the performance, since the scheduler is idle during this time.
04143  *
04144  * This register can be reset by IOI reset or with USBDRD()_UCTL_CTL[UAHC_RST].
04145  */
04146 union cvmx_usbdrdx_uahc_gtxthrcfg {
04147     uint32_t u32;
04148     struct cvmx_usbdrdx_uahc_gtxthrcfg_s {
04149 #ifdef __BIG_ENDIAN_BITFIELD
04150     uint32_t reserved_30_31               : 2;
04151     uint32_t usbtxpktcntsel               : 1;  /**< USB transmit packet-count enable. Enables/disables the USB transmission multipacket
04152                                                          thresholding:
04153                                                          0 = USB transmission multipacket thresholding is disabled, the core can only start
04154                                                          transmission on the USB after the entire packet has been fetched into the corresponding
04155                                                          TXFIFO.
04156                                                          1 = USB transmission multipacket thresholding is enabled. The core can only start
04157                                                          transmission on the USB after USBTXPKTCNT amount of packets for the USB transaction
04158                                                          (burst) are already in the corresponding TXFIFO. This mode is only valid in host mode.
04159                                                          This mode is only used for SuperSpeed. */
04160     uint32_t reserved_28_28               : 1;
04161     uint32_t usbtxpktcnt                  : 4;  /**< USB transmit-packet count. Specifies the number of packets that must be in the TXFIFO
04162                                                          before the core can start transmission for the corresponding USB transaction (burst). This
04163                                                          field is only valid when [USBTXPKTCNTSEL] = 1. Valid values are from 0x1 to 0xF.
04164                                                          This field must be <= [USBMAXTXBURSTSIZE]. */
04165     uint32_t usbmaxtxburstsize            : 8;  /**< USB maximum TX burst size. When [USBTXPKTCNTSEL] = 1, this field specifies the
04166                                                          maximum bulk OUT burst the core should do. When the system bus is slower than
04167                                                          the USB, TX FIFO can underrun during a long burst. Program a smaller value to
04168                                                          this field to limit the TX burst size that the core can do. It only applies to
04169                                                          SuperSpeed bulk, isochronous, and interrupt OUT endpoints in the host
04170                                                          mode. Valid values are from 0x1 to 0x10. */
04171     uint32_t reserved_0_15                : 16;
04172 #else
04173     uint32_t reserved_0_15                : 16;
04174     uint32_t usbmaxtxburstsize            : 8;
04175     uint32_t usbtxpktcnt                  : 4;
04176     uint32_t reserved_28_28               : 1;
04177     uint32_t usbtxpktcntsel               : 1;
04178     uint32_t reserved_30_31               : 2;
04179 #endif
04180     } s;
04181     struct cvmx_usbdrdx_uahc_gtxthrcfg_s  cn70xx;
04182     struct cvmx_usbdrdx_uahc_gtxthrcfg_s  cn70xxp1;
04183     struct cvmx_usbdrdx_uahc_gtxthrcfg_s  cn73xx;
04184     struct cvmx_usbdrdx_uahc_gtxthrcfg_s  cnf75xx;
04185 };
04186 typedef union cvmx_usbdrdx_uahc_gtxthrcfg cvmx_usbdrdx_uahc_gtxthrcfg_t;
04187 
04188 /**
04189  * cvmx_usbdrd#_uahc_guctl
04190  *
04191  * This register provides a few options for the software to control the core behavior in the host
04192  * mode. Most of the options are used to improve host inter-operability with different devices.
04193  *
04194  * This register can be reset by IOI reset or with USBDRD()_UCTL_CTL[UAHC_RST].
04195  */
04196 union cvmx_usbdrdx_uahc_guctl {
04197     uint32_t u32;
04198     struct cvmx_usbdrdx_uahc_guctl_s {
04199 #ifdef __BIG_ENDIAN_BITFIELD
04200     uint32_t refclkper                    : 10; /**< Reference-clock period. Indicates (in terms of ns) the period of REF_CLK. The default
04201                                                          value is set to 0x8
04202                                                          (8 ns/125 MHz). This field must be updated during power on initialization if
04203                                                          USBDRD()_UAHC_GCTL[SOFITPSYNC] = 1 or USBDRD()_UAHC_GFLADJ [GFLADJ_REFCLK_LPM_SEL] = 1.
04204                                                          The
04205                                                          programmable maximum value 62 ns, and the minimum value is 8 ns. You use a reference clock
04206                                                          with a period that is a integer multiple, so that ITP can meet the jitter margin of 32 ns.
04207                                                          The allowable REF_CLK frequencies whose period is not integer multiples are
04208                                                          16/17/19.2/24/39.7 MHz.
04209                                                          This field should not be set to 0x0 at any time. If you do not plan to use this feature,
04210                                                          then you need to set this field to 0x8, the default value. */
04211     uint32_t noextrdl                     : 1;  /**< No extra delay between SOF and the first packet.
04212                                                          Some high-speed devices misbehave when the host sends a packet immediately after an SOF.
04213                                                          However, adding an extra delay between an SOF and the first packet can reduce the USB data
04214                                                          rate and performance.
04215                                                          This bit is used to control whether the host should wait for 2 us before it sends the
04216                                                          first packet after a SOF, or not. You can set this bit to 1 to improve the performance if
04217                                                          those problematic devices are not a concern in your host environment.
04218                                                          0 = host waits for 2 us after an SOF before it sends the first USB packet.
04219                                                          1 = host does not wait after an SOF before it sends the first USB packet. */
04220     uint32_t psqextrressp                 : 3;  /**< PSQ extra reserved space. This is a debug feature, and is not intended for normal usage.
04221                                                          This parameter specifies how much additional space in the PSQ (protocol-status queue) must
04222                                                          be reserved before the U3PTL initiates a new USB transaction and burst beats. */
04223     uint32_t sprsctrltransen              : 1;  /**< Sparse control transaction enable. Some devices are slow in responding to control
04224                                                          transfers. Scheduling multiple transactions in one microframe/frame can cause these
04225                                                          devices to misbehave. If this bit is set to 1, the host controller schedules transactions
04226                                                          for a control transfer in different microframes/frames. */
04227     uint32_t resbwhseps                   : 1;  /**< Reserving 85% bandwidth for high-speed periodic EPs. By default, host controller reserves
04228                                                          80% of the bandwidth for periodic EPs. If this bit is set, the bandwidth is relaxed to 85%
04229                                                          to accommodate two high-speed, high-bandwidth ISOC EPs.
04230                                                          USB 2.0 required 80% bandwidth allocated for ISOC traffic. If two high bandwidth ISOC
04231                                                          devices (HD webcams) are connected, and if each requires 1024-bytes * 3 packets per
04232                                                          microframe, then the bandwidth required is around 82%. If this bit is set to 1, it is
04233                                                          possible to connect two webcams of 1024 bytes * 3 payload per microframe each. Otherwise,
04234                                                          you may have to reduce the resolution of the webcams. */
04235     uint32_t cmdevaddr                    : 1;  /**< Compliance mode for device address. When set to 1, slot ID can have different value than
04236                                                          device address if max_slot_enabled < 128.
04237                                                          0 = Device address is equal to slot ID.
04238                                                          1 = Increment device address on each address device command.
04239                                                          The xHCI compliance requires this bit to be set to 1. The 0 mode is for debug purpose
04240                                                          only. This allows you to easily identify a device connected to a port in the Lecroy or
04241                                                          Eliisys trace during hardware debug.
04242                                                          This bit is used in host mode only. */
04243     uint32_t reserved_14_14               : 1;
04244     uint32_t enoverlapchk                 : 1;  /**< Enable check for LFPS overlap during remote Ux Exit. If this bit is set to:
04245                                                          0 = When the link exists U1/U2/U3 because of a remote exit, it does not look for an LFPS
04246                                                          overlap.
04247                                                          1 = The SuperSpeed link, when exiting U1/U2/U3, waits for either the remote link LFPS or
04248                                                          TS1/TS2 training symbols before it confirms that the LFPS handshake is complete. This is
04249                                                          done to handle the case where the LFPS glitch causes the link to start exiting from the
04250                                                          low power state. Looking for the LFPS overlap makes sure that the link partner also sees
04251                                                          the LFPS. */
04252     uint32_t extcapsupten                 : 1;  /**< External extended capability support enable. If disabled, a read
04253                                                          USBDRD()_UAHC_SUPTPRT3_DW0
04254                                                          [NEXTCAPPTR] returns 0 in the next capability pointer field. This indicates there are no
04255                                                          more capabilities. If enabled, a read to USBDRD()_UAHC_SUPTPRT3_DW0[NEXTCAPPTR] returns 4
04256                                                          in
04257                                                          the
04258                                                          next capability pointer field.
04259                                                          Always set to 0x0. */
04260     uint32_t insrtextrfsbodi              : 1;  /**< Insert extra delay between full-speed bulk OUT transactions. Some full-speed devices are
04261                                                          slow to receive bulk OUT data and can get stuck when there are consecutive bulk OUT
04262                                                          transactions with short inter-transaction delays. This bit is used to control whether the
04263                                                          host inserts extra delay between consecutive bulk OUT transactions to a full-speed
04264                                                          endpoint.
04265                                                          0 = Host does not insert extra delay.
04266                                                          Setting this bit to 1 reduces the bulk OUT transfer performance for most of the full-speed
04267                                                          devices.
04268                                                          1 = Host inserts about 12 us extra delay between consecutive bulk OUT transactions to an
04269                                                          full-speed endpoint to work around the device issue. */
04270     uint32_t dtct                         : 2;  /**< Device timeout coarse tuning. This field determines how long the host waits for a response
04271                                                          from device before considering a timeout.
04272                                                          The core first checks the [DTCT] value. If it is 0, then the timeout value is defined by
04273                                                          the
04274                                                          [DTFT]. If it is nonzero, then it uses the following timeout values:
04275                                                          0x0 = 0 us; use [DTFT] value instead.
04276                                                          0x1 = 500 us.
04277                                                          0x2 = 1.5 ms.
04278                                                          0x3 = 6.5 ms. */
04279     uint32_t dtft                         : 9;  /**< Device timeout fine tuning. This field determines how long the host waits for a response
04280                                                          from a device before considering a timeout. For [DTFT] to take effect, [DTCT] must be set
04281                                                          to
04282                                                          0x0.
04283                                                          The [DTFT] value specifies the number of 125 MHz clock cycles * 256 to count before
04284                                                          considering a device timeout. For the 125 MHz clock cycles (8 ns period), this is
04285                                                          calculated as follows:
04286                                                          _ [DTFT value] * 256 * 8 (ns)
04287                                                          0x2 = 2 * 256 * 8 -> 4 us.
04288                                                          0x5 = 5 * 256 * 8 -> 10 us.
04289                                                          0xA = 10 * 256 * 8 -> 20 us.
04290                                                          0x10 = 16 * 256 * 8 -> 32 us.
04291                                                          0x19 = 25 * 256 * 8 -> 51 us.
04292                                                          0x31 = 49 * 256 * 8 -> 100 us.
04293                                                          0x62 = 98 * 256 * 8 -> 200 us. */
04294 #else
04295     uint32_t dtft                         : 9;
04296     uint32_t dtct                         : 2;
04297     uint32_t insrtextrfsbodi              : 1;
04298     uint32_t extcapsupten                 : 1;
04299     uint32_t enoverlapchk                 : 1;
04300     uint32_t reserved_14_14               : 1;
04301     uint32_t cmdevaddr                    : 1;
04302     uint32_t resbwhseps                   : 1;
04303     uint32_t sprsctrltransen              : 1;
04304     uint32_t psqextrressp                 : 3;
04305     uint32_t noextrdl                     : 1;
04306     uint32_t refclkper                    : 10;
04307 #endif
04308     } s;

04524                                                          0x31 = 49 * 256 * 8 -> 100 us.
04525                                                          0x62 = 98 * 256 * 8 -> 200 us. */
04526 #else

04531     uint32_t enoverlapchk                 : 1;
04532     uint32_t usbdrdstinautoretryen        : 1;
04533     uint32_t cmdevaddr                    : 1;
04534     uint32_t resbwhseps                   : 1;
04535     uint32_t sprsctrltransen              : 1;
04536     uint32_t psqextrressp                 : 3;
04537     uint32_t noextrdl                     : 1;
04538     uint32_t refclkper                    : 10;
04539 #endif
04540     } cn73xx;
04541     struct cvmx_usbdrdx_uahc_guctl_cn73xx cnf75xx;

04625 /**
04626  * cvmx_usbdrd#_uahc_gusb2phycfg#
04627  *
04628  * This register is used to configure the core after power-on. It contains USB 2.0 and USB 2.0
04629  * PHY-related configuration parameters. The application must program this register before
04630  * starting any transactions on either the SoC bus or the USB. Per-port registers are
04631  * implemented.
04632  *
04633  * Do not make changes to this register after the initial programming.
04634  */
04635 union cvmx_usbdrdx_uahc_gusb2phycfgx {
04636     uint32_t u32;
04637     struct cvmx_usbdrdx_uahc_gusb2phycfgx_s {
04638 #ifdef __BIG_ENDIAN_BITFIELD
04639     uint32_t physoftrst                   : 1;  /**< PHY soft reset. Causes the usb2phy_reset signal to be asserted to reset a UTMI PHY. */
04640     uint32_t u2_freeclk_exists            : 1;  /**< Specifies whether your USB 2.0 PHY provides a free-running PHY clock, which is active when
04641                                                          the clock control input is active. If your USB 2.0 PHY provides a free-running PHY clock,
04642                                                          it must be connected to the utmi_clk[0] input. The remaining utmi_clk[n] must be connected
04643                                                          to the respective port clocks. The core uses the Port-0 clock for generating the internal
04644                                                          mac2 clock.
04645                                                          0 = USB 2.0 free clock does not exist.
04646                                                          1 = USB 2.0 free clock exists.
04647                                                          This field must be set to zero if you enable ITP generation based on the REF_CLK
04648                                                          counter, USBDRD()_UAHC_GCTL[SOFITPSYNC] = 1, or USBDRD()_UAHC_GFLADJ
04649                                                          [GFLADJ_REFCLK_LPM_SEL] =
04650                                                          1. */
04651     uint32_t ulpi_lpm_with_opmode_chk     : 1;  /**< Support the LPM over ULPI without NOPID token to the ULPI PHY. Always 0x0. */
04652     uint32_t reserved_19_28               : 10;
04653     uint32_t ulpiextvbusindicator         : 1;  /**< Reserved (unused in this configuration). */
04654     uint32_t ulpiextvbusdrv               : 1;  /**< Reserved (unused in this configuration). */
04655     uint32_t ulpiclksusm                  : 1;  /**< Reserved (unused in this configuration). */
04656     uint32_t ulpiautores                  : 1;  /**< Reserved (unused in this configuration). */
04657     uint32_t reserved_14_14               : 1;
04658     uint32_t usbtrdtim                    : 4;  /**< USB 2.0 turnaround time. Sets the turnaround time in PHY clock cycles. Specifies the
04659                                                          response time for a MAC request to the packet FIFO controller (PFC) to fetch data from the
04660                                                          DFIFO (SPRAM).
04661                                                          USB turnaround time is a critical certification criteria when using long cables and five
04662                                                          hub levels.
04663                                                          When the MAC interface is 8-bit UTMI+/ULPI, the required values for this field is 0x9. */
04664     uint32_t xcvrdly                      : 1;  /**< Transceiver delay.
04665                                                          Enables a delay between the assertion of the UTMI transceiver select signal (for
04666                                                          HighSpeed) and the assertion of the TxValid signal during a HighSpeed chirp.
04667                                                          When this bit is set to 1, a delay of approximately 2.5 us is introduced from
04668                                                          the time when the transceiver select is set to 0x0, to the time when the TxValid
04669                                                          is driven to 0 for sending the chirp-K. This delay is required for some UTMI PHYs.
04670                                                          This bit is only valid in device mode. */
04671     uint32_t enblslpm                     : 1;  /**< Enable utmi_sleep_n and utmi_l1_suspend_n. The application uses this field to control
04672                                                          utmi_sleep_n and utmi_l1_suspend_n assertion to the PHY in the L1 state.
04673                                                          0 = utmi_sleep_n and utmi_l1_suspend_n assertion from the core is not transferred to the
04674                                                          external PHY.
04675                                                          1 = utmi_sleep_n and utmi_l1_suspend_n assertion from the core is transferred to the
04676                                                          external PHY.
04677                                                          When hardware LPM is enabled, this bit should be set high for Port0. */
04678     uint32_t physel                       : 1;  /**< USB 2.0 high-speed PHY or USB 1.1 full-speed serial transceiver select. */
04679     uint32_t susphy                       : 1;  /**< Suspend USB2.0 high-speed/full-speed/low-speed PHY. When set, USB2.0 PHY enters suspend
04680                                                          mode if suspend conditions are valid. */
04681     uint32_t fsintf                       : 1;  /**< Full-speed serial-interface select. Always reads as 0x0. */
04682     uint32_t ulpi_utmi_sel                : 1;  /**< ULPI or UTMI+ select. Always reads as 0x0, indicating UTMI+. */
04683     uint32_t phyif                        : 1;  /**< PHY interface width: 1 = 16-bit, 0 = 8-bit.
04684                                                          All the enabled 2.0 ports should have the same clock frequency as Port0 clock frequency
04685                                                          (utmi_clk[0]).
04686                                                          The UTMI 8-bit and 16-bit modes cannot be used together for different ports at the same
04687                                                          time (i.e., all the ports should be in 8-bit mode, or all of them should be in 16-bit
04688                                                          mode). */
04689     uint32_t toutcal                      : 3;  /**< High-speed/full-speed timeout calibration.
04690                                                          The number of PHY clock cycles, as indicated by the application in this field, is
04691                                                          multiplied by a bit-time factor; this factor is added to the high-speed/full-speed
04692                                                          interpacket timeout duration in the core to account for additional delays introduced by
04693                                                          the PHY. This might be required, since the delay introduced by the PHY in generating the
04694                                                          linestate condition can vary among PHYs.
04695                                                          The USB standard timeout value for high-speed operation is 736 to 816 (inclusive) bit
04696                                                          times. The USB standard timeout value for full-speed operation is 16 to 18 (inclusive) bit
04697                                                          times. The application must program this field based on the speed of connection.
04698                                                          The number of bit times added per PHY clock are:
04699                                                          * High-speed operation:
04700                                                          - one 30-MHz PHY clock = 16 bit times.
04701                                                          - one 60-MHz PHY clock = 8 bit times.
04702                                                          * Full-speed operation:
04703                                                          - one 30-MHz PHY clock = 0.4 bit times.
04704                                                          - one 60-MHz PHY clock = 0.2 bit times.
04705                                                          - one 48-MHz PHY clock = 0.25 bit times. */
04706 #else
04707     uint32_t toutcal                      : 3;
04708     uint32_t phyif                        : 1;
04709     uint32_t ulpi_utmi_sel                : 1;
04710     uint32_t fsintf                       : 1;
04711     uint32_t susphy                       : 1;
04712     uint32_t physel                       : 1;
04713     uint32_t enblslpm                     : 1;
04714     uint32_t xcvrdly                      : 1;
04715     uint32_t usbtrdtim                    : 4;
04716     uint32_t reserved_14_14               : 1;
04717     uint32_t ulpiautores                  : 1;
04718     uint32_t ulpiclksusm                  : 1;
04719     uint32_t ulpiextvbusdrv               : 1;
04720     uint32_t ulpiextvbusindicator         : 1;
04721     uint32_t reserved_19_28               : 10;
04722     uint32_t ulpi_lpm_with_opmode_chk     : 1;
04723     uint32_t u2_freeclk_exists            : 1;
04724     uint32_t physoftrst                   : 1;
04725 #endif
04726     } s;

04734 /**
04735  * cvmx_usbdrd#_uahc_gusb3pipectl#
04736  *
04737  * This register is used to configure the core after power-on. It contains USB 3.0 and USB 3.0
04738  * PHY-related configuration parameters. The application must program this register before
04739  * starting any transactions on either the SoC bus or the USB. Per-port registers are
04740  * implemented.
04741  *
04742  * Do not make changes to this register after the initial programming.
04743  */
04744 union cvmx_usbdrdx_uahc_gusb3pipectlx {
04745     uint32_t u32;
04746     struct cvmx_usbdrdx_uahc_gusb3pipectlx_s {
04747 #ifdef __BIG_ENDIAN_BITFIELD
04748     uint32_t physoftrst                   : 1;  /**< USB3 PHY soft reset (PHYSoftRst). When set to 1, initiates a PHY soft reset. After setting
04749                                                          this bit to 1, the software needs to clear this bit. */
04750     uint32_t hstprtcmpl                   : 1;  /**< Host port compliance. Setting this bit to 1 enables placing the SuperSpeed port link into
04751                                                          a compliance state, which allows testing of the PIPE PHY compliance patterns without
04752                                                          having to have a test fixture on the USB 3.0 cable. By default, this bit should be set to
04753                                                          0.
04754                                                          In compliance-lab testing, the SuperSpeed port link enters compliance after failing the
04755                                                          first polling sequence after power on. Set this bit to 0 when you run compliance tests.
04756                                                          The sequence for using this functionality is as follows:
04757                                                          * Disconnect any plugged-in devices.
04758                                                          * Set USBDRD()_UAHC_USBCMD[HCRST] = 1 or power-on-chip reset.
04759                                                          * Set USBDRD()_UAHC_PORTSC()[PP] = 0.
04760                                                          * Set HSTPRTCMPL = 1. This places the link into compliance state.
04761                                                          To advance the compliance pattern, follow this sequence (toggle HSTPRTCMPL):
04762                                                          * Set HSTPRTCMPL = 0.
04763                                                          * Set HSTPRTCMPL = 1. This advances the link to the next compliance pattern.
04764                                                          To exit from the compliance state, set USBDRD()_UAHC_USBCMD[HCRST] = 1 or power-on-chip
04765                                                          reset. */
04766     uint32_t u2ssinactp3ok                : 1;  /**< P3 OK for U2/SS.Inactive:
04767                                                          0 = During link state U2/SS.Inactive, put PHY in P2 (default).
04768                                                          1 = During link state U2/SS.Inactive, put PHY in P3. */
04769     uint32_t disrxdetp3                   : 1;  /**< Disables receiver detection in P3. If PHY is in P3 and the core needs to perform receiver
04770                                                          detection:
04771                                                          0 = Core performs receiver detection in P3 (default).
04772                                                          1 = Core changes the PHY power state to P2 and then performs receiver detection. After
04773                                                          receiver detection, core changes PHY power state to P3. */
04774     uint32_t ux_exit_in_px                : 1;  /**< UX exit in Px:
04775                                                          0 = Core does U1/U2/U3 exit in PHY power state P0 (default behavior).
04776                                                          1 = Core does U1/U2/U3 exit in PHY power state P1/P2/P3 respectively.
04777                                                          This bit is added for SuperSpeed PHY workaround where SuperSpeed PHY injects a glitch on
04778                                                          pipe3_RxElecIdle while receiving Ux exit LFPS, and pipe3_PowerDown change is in progress. */
04779     uint32_t ping_enchance_en             : 1;  /**< Ping enhancement enable. When set to 1, the downstream-port U1-ping-receive timeout
04780                                                          becomes 500 ms instead of 300 ms. Minimum Ping.LFPS receive duration is 8 ns (one mac3_clk
04781                                                          cycle). This field is valid for the downstream port only. */
04782     uint32_t u1u2exitfail_to_recov        : 1;  /**< U1U2exit fail to recovery. When set to 1, and U1/U2 LFPS handshake fails, the LTSSM
04783                                                          transitions from U1/U2 to recovery instead of SS.inactive.
04784                                                          If recovery fails, then the LTSSM can enter SS.Inactive. This is an enhancement only. It
04785                                                          prevents interoperability issue if the remote link does not do the proper handshake. */
04786     uint32_t request_p1p2p3               : 1;  /**< Always request P1/P2/P3 for U1/U2/U3.
04787                                                          0 = if immediate Ux exit (remotely initiated, or locally initiated) happens, the core does
04788                                                          not request P1/P2/P3 power state change.
04789                                                          1 = the core always requests PHY power change from P0 to P1/P2/P3 during U0 to U1/U2/U3
04790                                                          transition. */
04791     uint32_t startrxdetu3rxdet            : 1;  /**< Start receiver detection in U3/Rx.Detect.
04792                                                          If DISRXDETU3RXDET is set to 1 during reset, and the link is in U3 or Rx.Detect state, the
04793                                                          core starts receiver detection on rising edge of this bit.
04794                                                          This bit is valid for downstream ports only, and this feature must not be enabled for
04795                                                          normal operation. */
04796     uint32_t disrxdetu3rxdet              : 1;  /**< Disable receiver detection in U3/Rx.Detect. When set to 1, the core does not do receiver
04797                                                          detection in U3 or Rx.Detect state. If STARTRXDETU3RXDET is set to 1 during reset,
04798                                                          receiver detection starts manually.
04799                                                          This bit is valid for downstream ports only, and this feature must not be enabled for
04800                                                          normal operation. */
04801     uint32_t delaypx                      : 3;  /**< Delay P1P2P3. Delay P0 to P1/P2/P3 request when entering U1/U2/U3 until (DELAYPX * 8)
04802                                                          8B10B error occurs, or Pipe3_RxValid drops to 0.
04803                                                          DELAYPXTRANSENTERUX must reset to 1 to enable this functionality. */
04804     uint32_t delaypxtransenterux          : 1;  /**< Delay PHY power change from P0 to P1/P2/P3 when link state changing from U0 to U1/U2/U3
04805                                                          respectively.
04806                                                          0 = when entering U1/U2/U3, transition to P1/P2/P3 without checking for Pipe3_RxElecIlde
04807                                                          and pipe3_RxValid.
04808                                                          1 = when entering U1/U2/U3, delay the transition to P1/P2/P3 until the pipe3 signals,
04809                                                          Pipe3_RxElecIlde is 1 and pipe3_RxValid is 0. */
04810     uint32_t suspend_en                   : 1;  /**< Suspend USB3.0 SuperSpeed PHY (Suspend_en). When set to 1, and if suspend conditions are
04811                                                          valid, the USB 3.0 PHY enters suspend mode. */
04812     uint32_t datwidth                     : 2;  /**< PIPE data width.
04813                                                          0x0 = 32 bits.
04814                                                          0x1 = 16 bits.
04815                                                          0x2 = 8 bits.
04816                                                          0x3 = reserved.
04817                                                          One clock cycle after reset, these bits receive the value seen on the pipe3_DataBusWidth.
04818                                                          This will always be 0x0. */
04819     uint32_t abortrxdetinu2               : 1;  /**< Abort RX Detect in U2. When set to 1, and the link state is U2, the core aborts receiver
04820                                                          detection if it receives U2 exit LFPS from the remote link partner.
04821                                                          This bit is for downstream port only. */
04822     uint32_t skiprxdet                    : 1;  /**< Skip RX detect. When set to 1, the core skips RX detection if pipe3_RxElecIdle is low.
04823                                                          Skip is defined as waiting for the appropriate timeout, then repeating the operation. */
04824     uint32_t lfpsp0algn                   : 1;  /**< LFPS P0 align. When set to 1:
04825                                                          * the core deasserts LFPS transmission on the clock edge that it requests Phy power state
04826                                                          0 when exiting U1, U2, or U3 low power states. Otherwise, LFPS transmission is asserted
04827                                                          one clock earlier.
04828                                                          * the core requests symbol transmission two pipe3_rx_pclks periods after the PHY asserts
04829                                                          PhyStatus as a result of the PHY switching from P1 or P2 state to P0 state.
04830                                                          For USB 3.0 host, this is not required. */
04831     uint32_t p3p2tranok                   : 1;  /**< P3 P2 transitions OK.
04832                                                          0 = P0 is always entered as an intermediate state during transitions between P2 and P3, as
04833                                                          defined in the PIPE3 specification.
04834                                                          1 = the core transitions directly from Phy power state P2 to P3 or from state P3 to P2.
04835                                                          According to PIPE3 specification, any direct transition between P3 and P2 is illegal. */
04836     uint32_t p3exsigp2                    : 1;  /**< P3 exit signal in P2. When set to 1, the core always changes the PHY power state to P2,
04837                                                          before attempting a U3 exit handshake. */
04838     uint32_t lfpsfilt                     : 1;  /**< LFPS filter. When set to 1, filter LFPS reception with pipe3_RxValid in PHY power state
04839                                                          P0, ignore LFPS reception from the PHY unless both pipe3_Rxelecidle and pipe3_RxValid are
04840                                                          deasserted. */
04841     uint32_t rxdet2polllfpsctrl           : 1;  /**< RX_DETECT to Polling.
04842                                                          0 = Enables a 400 us delay to start polling LFPS after RX_DETECT. This allows VCM offset
04843                                                          to settle to a proper level.
04844                                                          1 = Disables the 400 us delay to start polling LFPS after RX_DETECT. */
04845     uint32_t reserved_7_7                 : 1;
04846     uint32_t txswing                      : 1;  /**< TX swing. Refer to the PIPE3 specification. */
04847     uint32_t txmargin                     : 3;  /**< TX margin. Refer to the PIPE3 specification, table 5-3. */
04848     uint32_t txdeemphasis                 : 2;  /**< TX deemphasis. The value driven to the PHY is controlled by the LTSSM during USB3
04849                                                          compliance mode. Refer to the PIPE3 specification, table 5-3.
04850                                                          Use the following values for the appropriate level of de-emphasis (From pipe3 spec):
04851                                                          0x0 =   -6 dB de-emphasis, use USBDRD()_UCTL_PORT()_CFG_SS[PCS_TX_DEEMPH_6DB].
04852                                                          0x1 = -3.5 dB de-emphasis, use USBDRD()_UCTL_PORT()_CFG_SS[PCS_TX_DEEMPH_3P5DB].
04853                                                          0x2 =     No de-emphasis.
04854                                                          0x3 =     Reserved. */
04855     uint32_t elasticbuffermode            : 1;  /**< Elastic buffer mode. Refer to the PIPE3 specification, table 5-3. */
04856 #else
04857     uint32_t elasticbuffermode            : 1;
04858     uint32_t txdeemphasis                 : 2;
04859     uint32_t txmargin                     : 3;
04860     uint32_t txswing                      : 1;
04861     uint32_t reserved_7_7                 : 1;
04862     uint32_t rxdet2polllfpsctrl           : 1;
04863     uint32_t lfpsfilt                     : 1;
04864     uint32_t p3exsigp2                    : 1;
04865     uint32_t p3p2tranok                   : 1;
04866     uint32_t lfpsp0algn                   : 1;
04867     uint32_t skiprxdet                    : 1;
04868     uint32_t abortrxdetinu2               : 1;
04869     uint32_t datwidth                     : 2;
04870     uint32_t suspend_en                   : 1;
04871     uint32_t delaypxtransenterux          : 1;
04872     uint32_t delaypx                      : 3;

04875     uint32_t request_p1p2p3               : 1;
04876     uint32_t u1u2exitfail_to_recov        : 1;
04877     uint32_t ping_enchance_en             : 1;
04878     uint32_t ux_exit_in_px                : 1;

04883 #endif

05321  * For information on this register, refer to the xHCI Specification, v1.0, section 5.4.8. Port 1

05345     uint32_t pec                          : 1;  /**< Port enabled/disabled change. */
05346     uint32_t csc                          : 1;  /**< Connect status change. */

05678 /**
05679  * cvmx_usbdrd#_uahc_usblegctlsts
05680  *
05681  * For information on this register, refer to the xHCI Specification, v1.0, section 7.1.2. Note
05682  * that the SMI interrupts are not connected to anything in a CNXXXX configuration.
05683  *
05684  * This register can be reset by IOI reset,
05685  * or USBDRD()_UCTL_CTL[UAHC_RST],
05686  * or USBDRD()_UAHC_GCTL[CORESOFTRESET],
05687  * or USBDRD()_UAHC_USBCMD[HCRST], or USBDRD()_UAHC_USBCMD[LHCRST].
05688  */
05689 union cvmx_usbdrdx_uahc_usblegctlsts {
05690     uint32_t u32;
05691     struct cvmx_usbdrdx_uahc_usblegctlsts_s {
05692 #ifdef __BIG_ENDIAN_BITFIELD
05693     uint32_t smi_on_bar                   : 1;  /**< System management interrupt on BAR. Never generated. */
05694     uint32_t smi_on_pci_command           : 1;  /**< System management interrupt on PCI command. Never generated. */
05695     uint32_t smi_on_os_ownership          : 1;  /**< System management interrupt on OS ownership change. This bit is set to 1 whenever
05696                                                          USBDRD()_UAHC_USBLEGSUP[HC_OS_OWNED_SEMAPHORES] transitions. */
05697     uint32_t reserved_21_28               : 8;
05698     uint32_t smi_on_hostsystemerr         : 1;  /**< System-management interrupt on host-system error. Shadow bit of USBDRD()_UAHC_USBSTS[HSE].
05699                                                          Refer to
05700                                                          xHCI Section 5.4.2 for definition and effects of the events associated with this bit being
05701                                                          set to 1.
05702                                                          To clear this bit to a 0, system software must write a 1 to USBDRD()_UAHC_USBSTS[HSE]. */
05703     uint32_t reserved_17_19               : 3;
05704     uint32_t smi_on_event_interrupt       : 1;  /**< System-management interrupt on event interrupt. Shadow bit of USBDRD()_UAHC_USBSTS[EINT].
05705                                                          Refer to
05706                                                          xHCI Section 5.4.2 for definition. This bit automatically clears when [EINT] clears and
05707                                                          sets when [EINT] sets. */
05708     uint32_t smi_on_bar_en                : 1;  /**< System-management interrupt on BAR enable. */
05709     uint32_t smi_on_pci_command_en        : 1;  /**< System-management interrupt on PCI command enable. */
05710     uint32_t smi_on_os_ownership_en       : 1;  /**< System-management interrupt on OS ownership enable. */
05711     uint32_t reserved_5_12                : 8;
05712     uint32_t smi_on_hostsystemerr_en      : 1;  /**< System-management interrupt on host-system error enable */
05713     uint32_t reserved_1_3                 : 3;
05714     uint32_t usb_smi_en                   : 1;  /**< USB system-management interrupt enable. */
05715 #else
05716     uint32_t usb_smi_en                   : 1;
05717     uint32_t reserved_1_3                 : 3;
05718     uint32_t smi_on_hostsystemerr_en      : 1;
05719     uint32_t reserved_5_12                : 8;
05720     uint32_t smi_on_os_ownership_en       : 1;
05721     uint32_t smi_on_pci_command_en        : 1;
05722     uint32_t smi_on_bar_en                : 1;
05723     uint32_t smi_on_event_interrupt       : 1;
05724     uint32_t reserved_17_19               : 3;
05725     uint32_t smi_on_hostsystemerr         : 1;
05726     uint32_t reserved_21_28               : 8;
05727     uint32_t smi_on_os_ownership          : 1;
05728     uint32_t smi_on_pci_command           : 1;
05729     uint32_t smi_on_bar                   : 1;
05730 #endif
05731     } s;
05732     struct cvmx_usbdrdx_uahc_usblegctlsts_s cn70xx;
05733     struct cvmx_usbdrdx_uahc_usblegctlsts_s cn70xxp1;
05734     struct cvmx_usbdrdx_uahc_usblegctlsts_s cn73xx;
05735     struct cvmx_usbdrdx_uahc_usblegctlsts_s cnf75xx;
